SECTION 3. FINDINGS.
================================================================================

Congress finds the following:

--- Constitutional Basis ---

(1) The Constitution of the United States vests in Congress, under Article I,
Section 8, the power to provide for the common defense, to raise and support
armies, to maintain a navy, to make rules for the government and regulation of
the land and naval forces, and to make all laws necessary and proper for
carrying these powers into execution. These powers are granted for the purpose
of securing the safety and welfare of the American people, not for the purpose
of maintaining any particular global monetary arrangement or projecting military
power in service of private economic interests.

(2) The Preamble to the Constitution enumerates the purposes of the federal
government as including the establishment of justice, the insurance of domestic
tranquility, the provision for the common defense, the promotion of the general
welfare, and the securing of the blessings of liberty. A defense posture oriented
toward protecting petrodollar hegemony serves some of these purposes poorly and
others not at all, and no interpretation of the constitutional defense power can
sustain indefinitely a military posture whose costs are borne by the general
public while its primary benefits flow to the holders of dollar-denominated
financial assets.

(3) The Fifth Amendment to the Constitution prohibits the deprivation of liberty
without due process of law. Automated systems that make or substantially
determine governmental decisions affecting individual rights without meaningful
human review constitute a deprivation of liberty without the process that the
Constitution demands, and no efficiency argument can justify the replacement of
constitutionally required human judgment with algorithmic determination.

(4) The First and Fourth Amendments to the Constitution protect the freedom of
association and the right of the people to be secure against unreasonable
searches. Mass surveillance architectures, whether operated by governmental
actors directly or by private entities under governmental direction or
inducement, constitute ongoing violations of these protections at a scale
unprecedented in the history of constitutional governance.

--- The Strategic Rationale for Defense Posture Reorientation ---

(5) The military posture of the United States has been organized, since at
least the early 1970s, substantially around the protection and extension of the
petrodollar system: the arrangement by which global energy markets are
denominated in United States dollars, generating sustained global demand for
dollar-denominated assets and enabling the United States to finance its
government and trade deficits through the issuance of currency rather than
through the production of goods and services. The maintenance of this
arrangement has required the deployment of military force, the maintenance of
overseas basing infrastructure, and the cultivation of alliance and client
relationships whose primary purpose is the protection of dollar hegemony rather
than the mutual security of allied peoples.

(6) The resource upon which the petrodollar system depends, petroleum, is
finite. Its accessible reserves are being depleted at rates that no policy
can reverse, and the timeline of its displacement as the primary source of
global energy is determined not by political choice but by the accelerating
economics of renewable alternatives and the accumulating ecological
consequences of combustion. The scientific consensus on anthropogenic climate
change, established through decades of convergent empirical research, documents
that the combustion of fossil fuels is the primary driver of atmospheric
warming whose consequences include rising sea levels, intensifying extreme
weather events, disruption of agricultural systems, and the displacement of
human populations at scales that constitute security threats of the first order.
A defense posture organized around protecting access to a finite resource whose
combustion actively generates the conditions that defense posture is supposed
to prevent is not a rational security strategy; it is a strategy for accelerating
the threats it purports to address.

(7) The renewable energy alternatives displacing petroleum are structurally more
compatible with commons governance than fossil fuel systems have ever been.
Petroleum extraction requires centralized infrastructure, long-distance
distribution networks, and concentrations of capital that make it a natural
monopoly and a natural instrument of geopolitical leverage. Distributed renewable
generation, by contrast, is precisely the kind of resource that cooperative
microgrids, community energy enterprises, and federated commons networks are
designed to govern. The energy transition therefore represents not only an
environmental and ecological imperative but an institutional opportunity: the
progressive replacement of a resource whose scarcity and centralization
supported extractive power arrangements with resources whose distributed
abundance supports commons governance. The defense posture reorientation
established by this Act is designed to accompany and accelerate that transition
rather than to obstruct it.

(8) The strategic costs of petrodollar-dependent defense posture are not
theoretical. Recent American military and diplomatic involvement in the Persian
Gulf region, including operations and posturing connected to tensions over
navigation rights in the Strait of Hormuz, has subordinated American security
commitments to the protection of fossil fuel shipping lanes whose strategic
significance diminishes with every solar panel installed and every cooperative
microgrid energized. American economic and military pressure on Venezuela,
a nation whose primary geopolitical significance to the United States derives
from its petroleum reserves rather than from any genuine security relationship,
illustrates the same pattern: military and economic instruments deployed in
service of resource access rather than in service of the security and welfare
of the American people. Congress finds that a defense posture capable of
generating these commitments is a defense posture in need of fundamental
reorientation, and that the domestic commons infrastructure established by the
Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act creates, for the first
time, the material conditions under which that reorientation is strategically
coherent.

(9) The domestic commons infrastructure established by the Federal Resilience
and Decentralization Initiatives Act -- including distributed renewable energy
cooperatives, cooperative food systems, resilient local manufacturing, and the
Commons Credit monetary architecture -- constitutes a strategic hedge against
petrodollar fragility by providing communities with the material self-sufficiency
to maintain the Guaranteed Provision Standard regardless of the condition of
global currency markets or the availability of imported fossil fuels. As this
infrastructure matures and the commons economy's renewable energy capacity
grows, the strategic rationale for a defense posture oriented around petrodollar
protection and fossil fuel access diminishes correspondingly, creating the
conditions for a genuine reorientation of national security strategy toward
resilience-based defense. The full restructuring of American alliance obligations
in light of this reorientation is addressed in subsequent legislation anticipated
by Section 906(c) of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(10) A resilience-based defense posture, organized around the protection of
commons infrastructure, the deterrence of direct attacks on American territory
and allied commons institutions, and the reduction of the overseas military
footprint whose costs the American people bear without commensurate security
benefit, serves the constitutional mandate to provide for the common defense
more faithfully than the current power-projection posture, whose costs have
grown while its security returns have diminished and whose continued operation
requires the perpetuation of fossil fuel dependence that both economic and
ecological reality are already ending.

--- Automation, Labor, and the Commons ---

(11) Automated systems -- including artificial intelligence, machine learning,
robotics, and algorithmic decision-making platforms -- are progressively
displacing human labor across the full range of productive activities: in
manufacturing, logistics, agriculture, professional services, creative work,
and governance. The central question posed by this displacement is not whether
it will occur but who will capture the productivity gains it generates. Under
the current economic arrangement, those gains flow primarily to the owners of
the automated systems, while the workers whose labor is displaced bear the
costs of displacement without claim on the abundance automation creates.

(12) The commons economy established by the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act provides the institutional architecture for
a different answer to this question: automated systems deployed within the
Federated Network are governed as commons resources, their productivity gains
are distributed through improvements to the Guaranteed Provision Standard and
reductions in required labor contributions, and no individual or enterprise
may capture the benefits of commons-deployed automation at the expense of the
Commons Members whose collective infrastructure made the automation possible.

(13) The governance of automated systems is not only an economic question but a
security question. Automated systems controlling critical infrastructure --
energy grids, food production systems, water treatment, communications networks,
and financial settlement infrastructure -- represent potential vectors for both
foreign adversarial interference and domestic oligarchic capture. A nation that
allows its critical infrastructure automation to be governed by proprietary
platforms under the control of private actors has not secured its infrastructure;
it has simply transferred the security risk from foreign actors to domestic ones.

(14) The open-source, commons-governed automation architecture established by
this Act -- in which all automated systems deployed in commons-critical
infrastructure are transparent, auditable, and governed through the democratic
processes of the Federated Network -- constitutes a genuine security improvement
over both proprietary automation under private control and centralized
governmental automation under administrative control. Distributed, transparent,
community-governed automation is more resilient, more accountable, and more
difficult to capture or corrupt than either alternative.

--- Analytics Platforms and the Intelligence Commons ---

(15) The United States government has, over decades of investment in intelligence
community technology programs, funded the development of sophisticated data
integration and analytics platforms whose core capabilities -- the integration
of heterogeneous data sources, the production of coherent operational pictures
for complex decision-making, and the coordination of logistics and resource
flows -- are precisely the capabilities that federated commons networks require
to govern themselves effectively. The concentration of these capabilities in
proprietary platforms under the control of private defense contractors, many of
whose foundational technologies were developed through public investment, is
inconsistent with the principle that publicly funded capabilities should serve
public purposes.

(16) The commons analytics infrastructure established by this Act -- providing
Qualified Federated Networks with open-source, community-governed data
integration and decision-support tools -- does not replicate surveillance
capitalism within the commons. It replaces surveillance capitalism with
transparency-based commons governance, in which analytical capabilities serve
the communities that use them rather than the shareholders of the platforms that
provide them.

(17) The specific analytics platforms developed through intelligence community
investment -- including those whose foundational technologies trace to In-Q-Tel
and related intelligence community venture capital programs -- represent a
category of publicly funded intellectual property that is subject to the commons
recapture principles of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives
Act. The commons capture of these platforms, and their transformation into
open-source commons governance tools, serves both the purposes of that Act and
the national security interest in ensuring that the most powerful data
integration capabilities available are governed democratically rather than
proprietary.

--- Human Oversight of Automated Systems ---

(18) Automated systems are not capable of exercising the contextual judgment,
the ethical deliberation, or the democratic accountability that governance of
human communities requires. The empirical record of automated decision-making
in consequential domains -- including criminal justice risk assessment, social
benefit eligibility determination, hiring and credit decisions, and military
targeting -- demonstrates systematic bias, opacity, and the amplification of
existing injustices at scales that human decision-making could not achieve.
The prohibition on algorithmic governance of individual rights established by
this Act is not a rejection of automation as a tool; it is a protection of the
human deliberative processes that the Constitution requires and that the
commons governance architecture of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
Initiatives Act embodies.

(19) The Human-in-the-Loop Layer established under the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act reflects an empirical finding, confirmed by
the DARPA Systematizing Confidence in Open Research and Evidence program and
by the broader literature on automated decision-making, that human oversight
is not merely a procedural protection but a substantive improvement: human
reviewers applying contextual judgment to automated determinations produce
more accurate, more just, and more legitimate outcomes than automated systems
operating without that oversight, across the full range of consequential
decision domains.

--- This Act's Relationship to the Legislative Program ---

(20) This Act is the third of four legislative vehicles constituting a complete
transition program from the extractive, punitive, and militarist order to a
federated commons organized around abundance, restoration, and solidarity. The
Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act established the material
commons. The Human Reclamation and Community Restorative Act established the
social commons. This Act establishes the strategic commons: the defense posture,
automation governance, and analytics infrastructure that protect and extend what
the first two Acts built. The fourth Act, addressing NATO obligations and
international alliance restructuring in detail, is anticipated in the finding of
Section 906(c) of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act
and in the foreign policy coherence provision of Section 405 of the Human
Reclamation and Community Restorative Act.

(21) The defense posture reorientation established by this Act is made
strategically coherent by the domestic commons infrastructure that the Federal
Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act creates. A nation whose
communities possess distributed, locally governed capacity to generate energy,
produce food, manufacture essential goods, and coordinate resources through
resilient peer-to-peer networks does not require a military posture organized
around the protection of centralized corporate supply chains and dollar-
denominated commodity markets. The domestic resilience infrastructure is the
strategic foundation; this Act builds the security architecture on top of it.

(22) This Act does not create a new defense establishment or a new administrative
apparatus for automation governance from theoretical foundations. The defense
posture reorientation it authorizes builds upon the existing capabilities,
relationships, and institutional knowledge of the Department of Defense and the
intelligence community, redirecting them toward purposes consistent with the
commons values of this legislative program. The automation governance
architecture it establishes builds upon the open-source software commons,
the cooperative technology sector, and the commons analytics work already
underway in academic and civil society institutions, providing the legal
framework and public investment that allows what already exists at the margins
to function at national scale. The open-source commons already governs
technical infrastructure of extraordinary scale and consequence: the Apache
Software Foundation governs more than 350 open-source projects whose
software underlies the majority of internet servers worldwide; the Linux
Foundation governs the Linux kernel and hundreds of related projects on which
the majority of cloud computing infrastructure runs; the Mozilla Foundation has
sustained a commons-governed web browser and internet standards participation
for more than two decades. These institutions demonstrate, at scale and in
production, that commons governance of critical technical infrastructure is not
a theoretical proposition but an operational reality. The Analytics Commons
and Open-Source Automation Mandate established by this Act build upon this
demonstrated foundation rather than constructing a new institutional form from
scratch.

