TITLE I -- RESILIENCE-BASED DEFENSE POSTURE
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the statutory foundation for the
reorientation of United States national security doctrine from a posture of
global power projection organized around the protection of dollar-denominated
energy markets to a posture of resilience-based defense organized around the
protection of the territorial integrity of the United States, the security of
commons infrastructure, and the deterrence of direct attacks on the American
people and their allied commons partners. This Title does not diminish American
military capability. It redirects that capability toward missions that
genuinely serve the security and welfare of the American people, and away from
missions whose primary beneficiaries are the holders of dollar-denominated
financial assets and the operators of fossil fuel infrastructure. The force
structure transition authorized by this Title is phased, deliberate, and tied
to the maturation of the domestic commons infrastructure whose resilience is
the strategic foundation of the new posture. Nothing in this Title shall be
construed to authorize any reduction in the readiness or capability of the
Armed Forces to defend the territorial integrity of the United States against
direct attack.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 101. RESILIENCE-BASED DEFENSE POSTURE -- DECLARATION AND DOCTRINE.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) DECLARATION.-- It is hereby declared to be the policy of the United States
that the primary missions of the United States Armed Forces are:

    (1) the defense of the territorial integrity of the United States against
    direct attack by any foreign power or non-state actor;

    (2) the deterrence of attacks on the Strategic Commons Infrastructure of
    the Federated Network, as defined in Section 4(16) of this Act, and on
    the commons infrastructure of partner nations with whom the United States
    has entered bilateral or multilateral commons federation agreements pursuant
    to Section 1005 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives
    Act;

    (3) the protection of freedom of navigation and overflight in international
    waters and airspace, in concert with allied and partner nations, to the
    extent that such protection serves the genuine security interests of the
    United States and its allies rather than the commercial interests of fossil
    fuel exporters or dollar-denominated commodity traders;

    (4) the deterrence and, where necessary, defeat of weapons of mass
    destruction threats through the maintenance of a minimum credible nuclear
    deterrent and through active participation in multilateral nonproliferation
    and disarmament frameworks; and

    (5) humanitarian assistance and disaster relief, in support of civil
    authorities and allied governments, with particular priority given to
    responses to the climate-related disasters whose increasing frequency and
    severity the findings of this Act identify as a consequence of the fossil
    fuel dependence this Act is designed to end.

(b) MISSIONS NO LONGER CONSTITUTING PRIMARY DEFENSE POLICY.-- It is the policy
of the United States that the following activities, which have consumed
substantial defense resources without commensurate benefit to the security and
welfare of the American people, shall not constitute primary missions of the
United States Armed Forces:

    (1) the protection of fossil fuel extraction, processing, or distribution
    infrastructure owned or operated by private entities, whether domestic or
    foreign, except as incidental to the defense of allied territory or the
    protection of freedom of navigation under subsection (a)(3) of this Section;

    (2) the projection of military force to maintain the denomination of global
    energy markets in United States dollars or to deter the development of
    alternative monetary arrangements by foreign governments or international
    institutions;

    (3) the conduct of regime change operations, covert destabilization programs,
    or military interventions whose primary purpose is the installation or
    maintenance of governments favorable to American corporate resource
    interests rather than to the genuine security interests of the United States
    or the self-determination of the peoples concerned; and

    (4) the maintenance of overseas basing infrastructure whose strategic
    rationale derives primarily from its proximity to fossil fuel reserves or
    shipping routes rather than from a genuine mutual security relationship with
    the host nation.

(c) DOCTRINAL REVIEW.-- Within one year of the date of enactment of this Act,
the Secretary of Defense shall conduct a comprehensive review of the National
Defense Strategy, the National Military Strategy, and all subordinate strategic
guidance documents, and shall revise those documents to reflect the Resilience-
Based Defense Posture declared in subsection (a) of this Section. The revised
documents shall:

    (1) identify each current mission, deployment, basing arrangement, and
    alliance commitment of the United States Armed Forces;

    (2) assess each identified item against the primary missions established
    in subsection (a) of this Section and the missions no longer constituting
    primary defense policy under subsection (b) of this Section;

    (3) recommend a phased transition plan for each deployment, basing
    arrangement, or alliance commitment that does not align with the primary
    missions of subsection (a), with transition timelines tied to the
    maturation benchmarks established in Section 103 of this Title; and

    (4) identify the force structure changes, basing consolidations, and
    procurement modifications necessary to implement the Resilience-Based
    Defense Posture within the transition timeline established in Section 103
    of this Title.

(d) REPORT TO CONGRESS.-- The Secretary of Defense shall submit the revised
strategic guidance documents and the phased transition plan required by
subsection (c) of this Section to the congressional defense committees within
thirty days of their completion. The submission shall include a classified
annex addressing sensitive operational details and an unclassified summary
suitable for public release, recorded on the National Resilience Ledger as
part of the commons governance history of this legislative program.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 102. COMMONS INFRASTRUCTURE PROTECTION AS DEFENSE MISSION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDING.-- Congress finds that the Strategic Commons Infrastructure of the
Federated Network constitutes critical national infrastructure whose disruption
by foreign adversarial action, domestic sabotage, or cyberattack would impair
the delivery of the Guaranteed Provision Standard to Commons Members and
undermine the material resilience that this legislative program is designed to
build. The protection of this infrastructure is therefore a genuine national
security mission, distinct from and additional to the conventional military
missions of territorial defense and force-on-force deterrence.

(b) COMMONS INFRASTRUCTURE THREAT ASSESSMENT.-- Within one hundred eighty days
of the date of enactment of this Act, the Secretary of Defense, acting in
coordination with the Director of National Intelligence and the Director of
the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency, shall complete a
comprehensive threat assessment identifying:

    (1) the specific categories of foreign adversarial action, including
    cyberattack, supply chain interdiction, electromagnetic pulse attack,
    and physical sabotage, that pose the greatest risks to the Strategic
    Commons Infrastructure of the Federated Network;

    (2) the specific vulnerabilities in the commons infrastructure architecture
    -- including the Federated Mesh, the National Resilience Ledger, cooperative
    energy microgrids, and commons food and water systems -- that are most
    susceptible to exploitation by the identified threat categories;

    (3) the defensive measures, both technical and operational, that would most
    effectively reduce the identified vulnerabilities, with particular attention
    to measures consistent with the distributed, open-source architecture of
    the Federated Network; and

    (4) the interface between the Department of Defense's existing critical
    infrastructure protection programs and the specific security requirements
    of the commons infrastructure established by the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(c) COMMONS INFRASTRUCTURE DEFENSE PROGRAM.-- Within one year of the completion
of the threat assessment required by subsection (b) of this Section, the
Secretary of Defense shall establish a Commons Infrastructure Defense Program
providing:

    (1) dedicated cyber defense support for the Federated Mesh and the National
    Resilience Ledger, including threat intelligence sharing between the
    Department of Defense and certified Qualified Federated Networks on a
    voluntary, consent-based basis consistent with the privacy protections of
    Title IV of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act;

    (2) hardening support for cooperative energy microgrids and other commons
    infrastructure against electromagnetic pulse and directed energy threats,
    drawing upon the dual-use technology transfer provisions of Title IX of
    the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act;

    (3) training and exercise programs for Qualified Federated Networks in
    resilience operations under degraded infrastructure conditions, including
    the Local Resilience Mode protocols established under Section 704(b) of
    the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act; and

    (4) a rapid response capability for commons infrastructure restoration
    following attack or natural disaster, staffed by military engineers and
    technicians with expertise in distributed energy, water, and communications
    systems, available to assist certified Qualified Federated Networks upon
    request.

(d) GOVERNANCE OF COMMONS INFRASTRUCTURE DEFENSE.-- The Commons Infrastructure
Defense Program established under subsection (c) of this Section shall be
governed by the following principles, ensuring that defense support for the
Federated Network does not replicate within the commons the surveillance and
control relationships that this legislative program is designed to replace:

    (1) all defense support provided to a Qualified Federated Network under
    this Section shall be provided upon the network's voluntary request and
    shall not be conditioned on any governance, operational, or reporting
    requirement beyond those already established under the Federal Resilience
    and Decentralization Initiatives Act;

    (2) no element of the Department of Defense or the Intelligence Community
    shall use the Commons Infrastructure Defense Program as a vehicle for
    collecting intelligence on the governance, membership, resource flows, or
    political activities of any Qualified Federated Network or its members;

    (3) threat intelligence shared with Qualified Federated Networks under
    paragraph (1) of subsection (c) of this Section shall be provided in
    forms that enable the network to defend its infrastructure without
    disclosing sources, methods, or classified operational details; and

    (4) the Commons Infrastructure Defense Program shall be subject to annual
    oversight review by the congressional intelligence and armed services
    committees, with a public summary of the review recorded on the National
    Resilience Ledger.

