SEC. 103. FORCE STRUCTURE TRANSITION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) PURPOSE.-- The force structure transition established by this Section
provides the phased, conditions-based framework within which the Department of
Defense realigns its basing, deployment, and procurement posture to reflect
the Resilience-Based Defense Posture declared in Section 101 of this Title.
The transition is deliberately tied to the maturation of the domestic commons
infrastructure, ensuring that reductions in the overseas military footprint
occur as the strategic rationale for that footprint diminishes rather than
before it does. No transition milestone under this Section shall be implemented
if the Secretary of Defense certifies to Congress, with specific written
findings, that implementation would create an unacceptable gap in the
genuine security commitments identified in Section 101(a) of this Title.

(b) PHASE 1 -- FOSSIL FUEL MISSION REDUCTION (YEARS 1 THROUGH 5).-- During
the five-year period following the date of enactment of this Act, the
Department of Defense shall:

    (1) complete the doctrinal review required by Section 101(c) of this Title
    and publish the revised National Defense Strategy reflecting the Resilience-
    Based Defense Posture;

    (2) identify and begin the drawdown of basing and deployment arrangements
    whose primary strategic rationale, as assessed under Section 101(c)(2) of
    this Title, is the protection of fossil fuel infrastructure or the
    maintenance of petrodollar arrangements rather than the genuine security
    missions of Section 101(a);

    (3) redirect not less than ten percent of the annual defense budget savings
    realized through basing consolidations and deployment drawdowns during this
    phase to the Bootstrap Grant Program established under Section 106 of the
    Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, accelerating the
    domestic commons infrastructure whose maturation is the strategic foundation
    of the Resilience-Based Defense Posture; and

    (4) complete the dual-use technology transfer program of Title IX of the
    Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, ensuring that the
    civilian commons infrastructure receives the full benefit of publicly funded
    defense research before the completion of Phase 1.

(c) PHASE 2 -- RESILIENCE POSTURE CONSOLIDATION (YEARS 5 THROUGH 10).--
During the period from the fifth through the tenth year following the date of
enactment of this Act, and contingent upon the Federated Network having achieved
the coverage and provision delivery benchmarks established in the network
maturity threshold of Section 107(f) of the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act, the Department of Defense shall:

    (1) complete the realignment of overseas basing to a configuration
    consistent with the genuine security missions of Section 101(a) of this
    Title, with the specific basing configuration determined through the alliance
    consultation processes anticipated in the fourth legislative vehicle of this
    program;

    (2) redirect not less than twenty percent of the cumulative annual defense
    budget savings realized through Phase 1 and Phase 2 realignments to the
    Bootstrap Grant Program and the Commons Solidarity Fund established under
    Section 1005 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act;
    and

    (3) complete the development and deployment of the Commons Infrastructure
    Defense Program established under Section 102(c) of this Title, ensuring
    that the Federated Network has full access to the defense support available
    under that program.

(d) PHASE 3 -- STEADY-STATE RESILIENCE POSTURE (YEAR 10 AND BEYOND).-- From
the tenth year following the date of enactment of this Act, the Department of
Defense shall maintain a steady-state force structure calibrated to the
Resilience-Based Defense Posture, subject to periodic review by the Secretary
of Defense and revision through the normal National Defense Strategy process,
with any proposed expansion of the force structure beyond the steady-state
configuration requiring a specific congressional authorization identifying the
genuine security mission that the expansion serves.

(e) DEFENSE SAVINGS ACCOUNTABILITY.-- The Secretary of Defense shall report
to Congress annually on:

    (1) the specific basing and deployment changes made during the preceding
    year under this Section, including the missions discontinued and the
    resources realigned;

    (2) the total annual defense budget savings attributable to the force
    structure transition, calculated against the baseline defense budget in
    the fiscal year preceding the date of enactment;

    (3) the amounts redirected to the Bootstrap Grant Program and the Commons
    Solidarity Fund pursuant to subsections (b)(3) and (c)(2) of this Section;
    and

    (4) an assessment of whether the implemented transition has created any gap
    in the genuine security commitments of Section 101(a) of this Title, with
    specific findings supporting any such assessment.

(f) NUCLEAR POSTURE.-- Nothing in this Title shall be construed to alter the
nuclear posture of the United States except as follows:

    (1) the Secretary of Defense, in the doctrinal review required by Section
    101(c) of this Title, shall assess the current nuclear posture against the
    primary missions of Section 101(a) of this Title and shall identify any
    nuclear capabilities or deployment arrangements whose primary rationale
    derives from petrodollar protection rather than from the maintenance of
    minimum credible deterrence; and

    (2) the Secretary of State is hereby authorized to pursue active engagement
    in multilateral nuclear disarmament negotiations under the existing
    framework of the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons,
    consistent with the longstanding American commitment to the goal of a
    world free of nuclear weapons, with a report to Congress on the status of
    those negotiations submitted annually beginning one year after the date of
    enactment of this Act.

