SEC. 104. INTELLIGENCE APPARATUS REFORM.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDING.-- Congress finds that elements of the United States Intelligence
Community have, over the course of their operational history, developed
capabilities and conducted activities -- including mass surveillance of domestic
and foreign communications, covert interference in the political processes of
foreign nations, and the maintenance of data collection programs whose scope
far exceeds what any legitimate security mission requires -- that are
inconsistent with the constitutional values of this legislative program, with
the privacy architecture of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
Initiatives Act, and with the commons solidarity principles of the Human
Reclamation and Community Restorative Act. The intelligence reform provisions
of this Section are not a diminishment of the Intelligence Community's capacity
to protect the genuine security interests of the United States; they are a
reorientation of that capacity toward missions that serve those interests and
away from missions that serve other interests at the expense of the rights and
welfare of the American people and of foreign peoples.

(b) MASS SURVEILLANCE TERMINATION.-- Within one year of the date of enactment
of this Act:

    (1) all programs of the Intelligence Community that involve the bulk
    collection of communications metadata, content, or associated data of
    United States persons without individualized judicial authorization meeting
    the probable cause standard of the Fourth Amendment shall be terminated;

    (2) all data collected through the programs terminated under paragraph (1)
    of this subsection shall be deleted from all Intelligence Community systems,
    with deletion certified to Congress by the Inspector General of the
    Intelligence Community within ninety days of the termination date;

    (3) no element of the Intelligence Community shall enter into any agreement,
    formal or informal, with any private technology company, data broker, or
    foreign intelligence service for the purpose of obtaining access to bulk
    communications data of United States persons through means that would not
    be available through direct collection under the standards of paragraph (1)
    of this subsection; and

    (4) no order of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Court issued or
    renewed after the date of enactment of this Act shall authorize bulk
    collection inconsistent with paragraph (1) of this subsection, and any
    outstanding order authorizing such collection shall lapse upon its
    current expiration date without renewal. The conforming amendment to
    the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act established in Section 506(b)
    of this Act shall be construed as superseding any conflicting provision
    of that Act with respect to orders issued or renewed after the date of
    enactment of this Act.

(c) COVERT INTERFERENCE PROHIBITION.-- No element of the Intelligence Community
shall conduct, fund, direct, or provide material support for any covert program
whose purpose is:

    (1) the overthrow, destabilization, or manipulation of the government of
    any foreign nation, except upon a specific finding by the President,
    transmitted to the congressional intelligence committees under the
    notification requirements of the National Security Act of 1947, that the
    targeted government poses a direct and imminent military threat to the
    territorial integrity of the United States and that covert action is the
    minimum necessary response; or

    (2) the suppression of commons institution development, cooperative
    enterprise formation, solidarity economy organizing, or any other activity
    consistent with the values of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
    Initiatives Act in any foreign nation, consistent with the prohibition on
    export of carceral and surveillance technology established in Section 404(d)
    of the Human Reclamation and Community Restorative Act.

(d) REORIENTATION TOWARD COMMONS SECURITY.-- The Intelligence Community shall
reorient a defined portion of its collection, analysis, and operational capacity
toward the following missions consistent with the Resilience-Based Defense
Posture:

    (1) identification and assessment of foreign adversarial threats to the
    Strategic Commons Infrastructure of the Federated Network, including
    cyberattack capabilities, supply chain interdiction programs, and
    electromagnetic attack technologies;

    (2) monitoring of foreign state and non-state actor programs for the
    development or acquisition of weapons of mass destruction, in support of
    the nonproliferation mission of Section 101(a)(4) of this Title;

    (3) assessment of the climate-related security threats identified in Finding
    6 of Section 3 of this Act, including the displacement, resource conflict,
    and governance instability consequences of accelerating ecological
    disruption; and

    (4) support for the Commons Solidarity Fund established under Section 1005
    of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, through
    open-source analysis of the conditions affecting commons institution
    development in partner nations, without covert interference in those nations'
    internal political processes.

(e) OVERSIGHT AND ACCOUNTABILITY.-- The intelligence reforms established by this
Section shall be subject to the following oversight mechanisms:

    (1) the Inspector General of the Intelligence Community shall conduct an
    annual audit of compliance with the mass surveillance termination requirement
    of subsection (b) and the covert interference prohibition of subsection (c),
    with the unclassified portions of each audit report published on the National
    Resilience Ledger;

    (2) the congressional intelligence committees shall conduct annual oversight
    hearings on the implementation of this Section, with public testimony from
    the Director of National Intelligence on the progress of the intelligence
    reorientation required by subsection (d); and

    (3) any Intelligence Community element found by the Inspector General to have
    violated the requirements of subsection (b) or subsection (c) shall be
    subject to the remedial authorities of the Inspector General Act of 1978,
    and the Director of National Intelligence shall report the violation and the
    remedial actions taken to Congress within thirty days of the Inspector
    General's finding.

================================================================================
TITLE II -- COMMONS NETWORK SECURITY
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the legal architecture through which
the Federated Network protects itself against the specific threat categories
that a commons economy faces: foreign adversarial interference with commons
infrastructure, domestic attempts to capture or re-enclose commons assets
through technical means, sabotage of the National Resilience Ledger or the
Federated Mesh, and the infiltration of commons governance by actors whose
purpose is disruption rather than participation. These threats are distinct
from the conventional military threats addressed in Title I, and they require
governance responses that are themselves consistent with the commons values of
this legislative program: distributed, transparent, peer-governed, and
resistant to capture by any single actor including the federal government.
The security architecture of this Title is not a surveillance architecture.
It does not create new governmental authorities to monitor commons members or
commons governance. It creates the legal framework within which the Federated
Network's own distributed security mechanisms, established under the Federal
Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, are recognized, resourced,
and protected from interference.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 201. COMMONS INFRASTRUCTURE AS CRITICAL NATIONAL INFRASTRUCTURE.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) DESIGNATION.-- The Strategic Commons Infrastructure of the Federated
Network, as defined in Section 4(16) of this Act, is hereby designated as
critical national infrastructure within the meaning of Presidential Policy
Directive 21 and any successor policy, entitled to the full range of federal
critical infrastructure protection support, information sharing, and security
assistance available to other designated critical infrastructure sectors.

(b) SECTOR DESIGNATION.-- The Secretary of Homeland Security shall, within
one hundred eighty days of the date of enactment of this Act, formally
designate the Federated Commons Infrastructure as a critical infrastructure
sector and shall:

    (1) assign a Sector Risk Management Agency with relevant expertise in
    distributed energy, cooperative governance, and open-source technology
    systems, which shall not be the Department of Defense or any element of
    the Intelligence Community;

    (2) establish a Commons Infrastructure Sector Coordinating Council
    comprising representatives of certified Qualified Federated Networks,
    selected through the governance processes of the Federated Network, which
    shall serve as the primary interface between the commons sector and federal
    critical infrastructure protection programs;

    (3) ensure that the Information Sharing and Analysis Center framework
    available to other critical infrastructure sectors is extended to the
    Commons Infrastructure sector, with information sharing conducted through
    the Federated Mesh rather than through centralized governmental databases,
    consistent with the privacy architecture of Title IV of the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act; and

    (4) publish annual sector risk assessments, in coordination with the Commons
    Infrastructure Sector Coordinating Council, with unclassified summaries
    recorded on the National Resilience Ledger and accessible to all Commons
    Members.

(c) FEDERAL SUPPORT OBLIGATIONS.-- As a designated critical infrastructure
sector, the Federated Commons Infrastructure shall be entitled to:

    (1) priority consideration in federal cybersecurity assistance programs
    administered by the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency,
    including vulnerability assessments, penetration testing support, and
    incident response assistance, provided on a voluntary request basis
    consistent with the governance principles of Section 102(d) of Title I
    of this Act;

    (2) access to federal threat intelligence relevant to the security of
    commons infrastructure, provided through the information sharing mechanisms
    of subsection (b)(3) of this Section, at the level of classification
    appropriate for sharing with non-governmental critical infrastructure
    operators; and

    (3) inclusion in federal emergency preparedness planning and exercises,
    with the Federated Network's Local Resilience Mode protocols recognized
    as a national emergency preparedness asset whose protection and
    strengthening serves the public interest.

(d) LIMITATION ON FEDERAL AUTHORITY.-- The designation of the Federated Commons
Infrastructure as critical national infrastructure under this Section shall not
be construed to:

    (1) grant any federal agency regulatory authority over the internal
    governance, resource allocation, or operational decisions of any Qualified
    Federated Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network beyond what is
    expressly authorized by the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
    Initiatives Act;

    (2) authorize any federal agency to require the installation of monitoring
    equipment, reporting mechanisms, or access controls in commons
    infrastructure beyond what the network has voluntarily adopted through
    its own collective-choice processes; or

    (3) create any basis for invoking emergency governmental authority over
    commons infrastructure, with the emergency resilience functions of the
    Federated Network governed exclusively through the Local Resilience Mode
    and systemic continuity provisions of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 202. FOREIGN ADVERSARIAL INTERFERENCE -- PROHIBITIONS AND RESPONSES.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) PROHIBITED CONDUCT.-- The following conduct is hereby prohibited and subject
to the criminal penalties established in Section 207 of this Title:

    (1) any act by or on behalf of a foreign government, foreign organization,
    or foreign person that is designed to disrupt, degrade, disable, or destroy
    the Federated Mesh, the National Resilience Ledger, or any component of
    the Strategic Commons Infrastructure, including through cyberattack,
    electromagnetic interference, physical sabotage, or supply chain
    interdiction;

    (2) any act designed to introduce fraudulent data, false resource signals,
    or spoofed Physical Unclonable Function signatures into the Federated Mesh
    for the purpose of manipulating the Asynchronous Resource Coordination
    protocol, the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism, or the Commons Credit
    transaction systems of the National Resilience Ledger;

    (3) any act designed to compromise the cryptographic integrity of the
    National Resilience Ledger, including attacks on the consensus mechanism,
    the validator node infrastructure, or the smart contract code governing
    automated commons transactions; and

    (4) any act designed to infiltrate the governance processes of a Qualified
    Federated Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network for the purpose of
    capturing, redirecting, or undermining the network's commons stewardship
    functions, including through the creation of fraudulent cooperative entities
    for the purpose of gaining network access and certification status.

(b) FEDERAL RESPONSE AUTHORITY.-- Upon a credible determination by the
Secretary of Defense or the Director of the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure
Security Agency that a foreign adversarial interference action described in
subsection (a) of this Section is underway or imminent, the following response
authorities are available:

    (1) the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency may provide
    immediate technical assistance to affected Qualified Federated Networks,
    upon their request, including active cyber defense support, forensic
    analysis, and incident response coordination;

    (2) the Department of Defense may take such defensive cyber actions as are
    authorized under existing law and the laws of armed conflict to neutralize
    the identified threat, with notification to the congressional defense and
    intelligence committees within forty-eight hours of any such action; and

    (3) the Secretary of State may invoke the diplomatic and economic response
    measures available under existing law, including the International Emergency
    Economic Powers Act, to impose costs on the foreign government or
    organization responsible for the interference action.

(c) NETWORK SELF-DEFENSE.-- Nothing in this Title shall be construed to limit
the authority of the Federated Network's own distributed security mechanisms,
established under the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act,
to defend against foreign adversarial interference through:

    (1) the Entropy Lock mechanism of Section 704(c) of that Act, which may
    be activated to isolate compromised network segments without federal
    authorization;

    (2) the Byzantine Fault Tolerant protocols of Section 704(d) of that Act,
    which maintain ledger integrity against coordinated validator node attacks;
    and

    (3) the Local Resilience Mode of Section 704(b) of that Act, which
    maintains provision delivery to Commons Members during periods of external
    network attack.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 203. DOMESTIC ENCLOSURE ATTEMPTS -- SECURITY CLASSIFICATION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDING.-- Congress finds that the most persistent long-term threat to the
integrity of the Federated Network is not foreign adversarial interference but
domestic enclosure: the systematic attempt by private actors, corporate
entities, or captured governmental authorities to convert commons assets to
private ownership, to re-enclose commons intellectual property through
proprietary claims, to capture commons governance through the accumulation of
disproportionate influence, or to use the commons infrastructure as a vector
for private data extraction. The security architecture of this Title must
address this domestic threat with the same seriousness it applies to foreign
threats, recognizing that the enclosure of commons assets by domestic actors
is no less destructive of the commons than their destruction by foreign ones.

(b) ENCLOSURE ATTEMPT DEFINED.-- For the purposes of this Title, a domestic
enclosure attempt means any deliberate, coordinated course of conduct by any
person, enterprise, or governmental actor that is designed to:

    (1) acquire title, exclusive control, or proprietary rights over land,
    intellectual property, data, or other assets held in commons stewardship
    by a Qualified Federated Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network,
    through means other than the lawful governance processes of the network;

    (2) assert intellectual property claims over works, innovations, or
    traditional knowledge contributed to the Intellectual Property Commons,
    in violation of the anti-enclosure provisions of Title V of the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act;

    (3) infiltrate the governance of a Qualified Federated Network through
    the creation of fraudulent cooperative memberships, the manipulation of
    collective-choice processes, or the systematic misrepresentation of resource
    data to the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism, for the purpose of diverting
    commons resources to private benefit; or

    (4) use access to commons infrastructure, including the Federated Mesh,
    the National Resilience Ledger, or the Analytics Commons established under
    Title III of this Act, to collect personal data on Commons Members for
    commercial, governmental, or other non-commons purposes, in violation of
    the data sovereignty protections of Title IV of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(c) ENFORCEMENT.-- Domestic enclosure attempts as defined in subsection (b)
of this Section shall be subject to:

    (1) the civil remedies available to Qualified Federated Networks and
    Commons Members under Section 101(d) of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act, including injunctive relief without bond;

    (2) the graduated response procedures of Section 103(c) of that Act,
    where the enclosure attempt is conducted by or through a certified entity
    subject to those procedures;

    (3) the criminal penalties established in Section 207 of this Title, where
    the enclosure attempt involves fraud, unauthorized computer access, or other
    conduct independently prohibited by federal criminal law; and

    (4) referral to the Department of Justice Antitrust Division where the
    enclosure attempt involves coordinated conduct by multiple actors designed
    to monopolize access to commons resources or to suppress the development
    of commons institutions as competitors to existing proprietary enterprises.

(d) GOVERNMENTAL ENCLOSURE PROHIBITION.-- No federal, state, or local
governmental authority shall:

    (1) invoke eminent domain, regulatory taking doctrine, or any other
    governmental power to transfer commons assets from Qualified Federated
    Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network stewardship to private ownership
    or governmental ownership, except as expressly authorized by the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act;

    (2) condition any governmental benefit, permit, license, or approval on
    the modification, reduction, or waiver of any commons governance right
    established under that Act or this Act; or

    (3) use any governmental data collection program, including programs
    operated by the Internal Revenue Service, the Securities and Exchange
    Commission, or any regulatory agency, to compile intelligence on the
    governance, membership, resource flows, or political activities of any
    Qualified Federated Network for purposes other than the specific regulatory
    function for which the data collection authority was granted.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 204. COMMONS SECURITY INFORMATION SHARING.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ARCHITECTURE.-- The commons security information sharing architecture
established by this Section shall operate entirely within the Federated Mesh,
using the privacy-preserving computation methods and Zero-Knowledge Proof
protocols of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act,
such that security-relevant information is shared among certified Qualified
Federated Networks without creating a centralized threat database accessible
to governmental authorities or private parties.

(b) PEER THREAT INTELLIGENCE.-- The Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism established
under Section 103 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives
Act is hereby extended to include a peer threat intelligence function, through
which:

    (1) a Qualified Federated Network that has identified a specific, credible
    threat to its commons infrastructure -- including a cyberattack, a physical
    sabotage attempt, a fraudulent certification application, or a coordinated
    enclosure attempt -- may broadcast a threat signal to neighboring networks
    through the Federated Mesh, without disclosing the identities of individuals
    involved in the threat or the specific operational details of the network's
    defensive response;

    (2) receiving networks may use the threat signal to activate heightened
    monitoring of the identified threat category within their own infrastructure,
    consistent with the Standard 4 monitoring requirements of Section 102(e)
    of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act; and

    (3) the Technical Standards Body established under Section 701(d) of that
    Act shall establish the technical specifications for threat signal formats,
    ensuring that threat signals carry sufficient information for defensive
    action while containing insufficient information to support surveillance
    of the Commons Members or governance activities of the broadcasting network.

(c) FEDERAL THREAT INTELLIGENCE INTERFACE.-- The Cybersecurity and
Infrastructure Security Agency shall establish a dedicated interface for
sharing declassified or unclassified threat intelligence with the Commons
Infrastructure Sector Coordinating Council established under Section 201(b)(2)
of this Title, on the following terms:

    (1) threat intelligence shared through this interface shall be provided
    in machine-readable formats compatible with the Federated Mesh Open Standard,
    enabling automated integration into the network's security monitoring
    without requiring the disclosure of the underlying intelligence sources or
    methods to network operators;

    (2) no condition, reporting requirement, or operational obligation shall
    be attached to the receipt of threat intelligence through this interface
    beyond the certification requirements already applicable to Qualified
    Federated Networks under the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
    Initiatives Act; and

    (3) the Commons Infrastructure Sector Coordinating Council shall publish
    an annual report on the utility and adequacy of the federal threat
    intelligence provided through this interface, with recommendations for
    improvement, recorded on the National Resilience Ledger.

(d) PROHIBITION ON WEAPONIZATION OF SECURITY INFRASTRUCTURE.-- The commons
security information sharing architecture established by this Section shall
not be used, by any governmental or private actor, as a vehicle for:

    (1) identifying, profiling, or targeting Commons Members on the basis of
    their governance participation, political activities, or associational
    relationships within the Federated Network;

    (2) collecting aggregate behavioral or demographic data on Commons Members
    under the guise of security monitoring; or

    (3) establishing any persistent surveillance capability within the Federated
    Network beyond the resource health monitoring already authorized under
    Standard 4 of Section 102(e) of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
    Initiatives Act.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 205. COMMONS SECURITY RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) OPEN-SOURCE SECURITY MANDATE.-- All security research, vulnerability
assessment, and defensive technology development funded through federal programs
for the protection of the Federated Commons Infrastructure shall be:

    (1) conducted through open-source methodologies wherever technically
    feasible, with research outputs contributed to the Intellectual Property
    Commons pursuant to the mandatory commons contribution provisions of Section
    503 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act;

    (2) coordinated with the Technical Standards Body established under Section
    701(d) of that Act to ensure that security improvements are incorporated
    into the Federated Mesh Open Standard through the standard's open governance
    process; and

    (3) made available to all certified Qualified Federated Networks
    simultaneously, without preferential access for any network, governmental
    entity, or private contractor.

(b) COMMONS SECURITY RESEARCH PROGRAM.-- The Director of the National Science
Foundation, in coordination with the Director of the National Institute of
Standards and Technology and the Director of the Cybersecurity and
Infrastructure Security Agency, shall establish a Commons Security Research
Program providing grants for open-source security research directly relevant
to the protection of the Federated Mesh, the National Resilience Ledger, and
the commons governance architecture, with priority given to research in:

    (1) privacy-preserving threat detection methods that identify adversarial
    interference without exposing Commons Member behavioral data;

    (2) Byzantine fault-tolerant consensus mechanisms applicable to the specific
    resource and governance coordination functions of the National Resilience
    Ledger;

    (3) hardware security enhancements to the Physical Unclonable Function
    architecture established under Section 702 of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act, maintaining unclonability as manufacturing
    capabilities advance; and

    (4) distributed intrusion detection systems operable within the Local
    Resilience Mode architecture, ensuring that commons security monitoring
    remains functional during periods of external network disruption.

(c) VULNERABILITY DISCLOSURE.-- Any researcher, Commons Member, or third party
who identifies a vulnerability in the Federated Mesh Open Standard, the National
Resilience Ledger, or any commons infrastructure technology shall have access
to a responsible disclosure pathway administered by the Technical Standards Body,
through which:

    (1) the vulnerability is reported confidentially to the Technical Standards
    Body and the relevant network operators;

    (2) a remediation timeline is established, not to exceed ninety days for
    critical vulnerabilities and one hundred eighty days for other
    vulnerabilities; and

    (3) upon completion of remediation, the vulnerability and its resolution
    are published on the National Resilience Ledger as part of the commons
    security knowledge base, contributing to the collective security of all
    networks without disclosing exploitable details during the remediation
    period.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 206. PROTECTION OF COMMONS GOVERNANCE FROM INFILTRATION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDING.-- Congress finds that the governance processes of a Qualified
Federated Network are as much a security asset as its technical infrastructure,
and that the infiltration of commons governance by actors whose purpose is
capture, diversion, or disruption represents a threat to the commons that is
not addressable through technical security measures alone. The governance
integrity provisions of this Section supplement the Ostrom Standards of
Stewardship and the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism of the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act with specific protections against the
deliberate manipulation of commons governance for anti-commons purposes.

(b) FOREIGN GOVERNMENTAL INFLUENCE PROHIBITION.-- No foreign government, foreign
governmental entity, or agent of a foreign government shall:

    (1) hold membership in any Qualified Federated Cooperative or Qualified
    Federated Network, or exercise governance rights within any such entity,
    whether directly or through any intermediary;

    (2) provide funding, in-kind support, or other material assistance to any
    Qualified Federated Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network for the
    purpose of influencing the governance decisions or resource allocation
    of that entity; or

    (3) use any representative, agent, or intermediary to participate in the
    collective-choice processes of any Qualified Federated Network without
    disclosing the foreign governmental relationship to the network's governance
    body.

(c) CORPORATE CAPTURE PREVENTION.-- The anti-concentration provisions of
Section 508 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act
are hereby extended to address the specific risk of corporate capture of
commons governance, providing that:

    (1) no corporation, private equity fund, hedge fund, or other entity
    organized primarily for the profit of its investors shall hold membership
    in any Qualified Federated Cooperative in a manner that grants governance
    rights within that cooperative;

    (2) no individual who holds, directly or through any intermediary, a
    controlling ownership interest in any corporation with annual revenues
    exceeding one billion dollars shall simultaneously hold governance rights
    in any Qualified Federated Network, except through membership in a
    Qualified Federated Cooperative in their capacity as a natural person
    residing or working within the cooperative's defined boundaries; and

    (3) any attempt to use shell memberships, nominee participation, or
    coordinated governance manipulation to concentrate commons governance
    influence in a manner inconsistent with the Ostrom Standards of Stewardship
    shall constitute a serious violation subject to Level 3 graduated response
    under Section 103(c)(2)(C) of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
    Initiatives Act.

(d) GOVERNANCE INTEGRITY MONITORING.-- The Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism
established under Section 103 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
Initiatives Act shall include governance integrity monitoring functions through
which auditing peers assess:

    (1) whether the audited network's collective-choice processes demonstrate
    genuine participation by the full membership rather than formal compliance
    masking effective concentration of governance authority;

    (2) whether the audited network's membership composition is consistent
    with the prohibitions of subsections (b) and (c) of this Section; and

    (3) whether any anomalous pattern in the audited network's governance
    decisions, resource flows, or reporting data is consistent with the
    indicators of governance capture identified in the threat intelligence
    shared through Section 204 of this Title.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 207. CRIMINAL PENALTIES.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) COMMONS INFRASTRUCTURE SABOTAGE.-- Chapter 65 of Title 18, United States
Code, is hereby amended to add the following offense: whoever knowingly and
willfully destroys, damages, disables, or substantially disrupts any component
of the Strategic Commons Infrastructure, the Federated Mesh, or the National
Resilience Ledger, or attempts or conspires to do so, shall be punished by
imprisonment of not more than twenty years, a fine of not more than five million
dollars, or both, if the conduct results in or is designed to result in a
material impairment of the Guaranteed Provision Standard for any number of
Commons Members; or by imprisonment of not more than ten years, a fine of not
more than one million dollars, or both, in all other cases.

(b) FRAUDULENT CERTIFICATION.-- Whoever knowingly makes any false statement,
representation, or certification in connection with any application for
Qualified Federated Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network certification
under the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, or knowingly
uses any fraudulent means to obtain or maintain certification status, shall be
punished by imprisonment of not more than five years, a fine of not more than
five hundred thousand dollars, or both.

(c) COMMONS GOVERNANCE INFILTRATION.-- Whoever knowingly violates the foreign
governmental influence prohibition of Section 206(b) of this Title, or
knowingly participates in a coordinated scheme to capture commons governance
in violation of Section 206(c) of this Title, shall be punished by imprisonment
of not more than ten years, a fine of not more than one million dollars, or
both.

(d) PROTECTED DISCLOSURE.-- No provision of this Section shall be construed
to prohibit or penalize any Commons Member, researcher, or whistleblower who
in good faith discloses information about a potential violation of this Title
to the Office of Federated Stewardship, the Federated Accountability Board,
Congress, or any appropriate oversight authority, consistent with the
whistleblower protections of Section 107(g)(3) of the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act.

================================================================================
TITLE III -- THE ANALYTICS COMMONS
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the open-source, community-governed
data integration and decision-support infrastructure that federated commons
networks require to coordinate their resource flows, govern their commons
assets, and plan for their communities' long-term resilience. The Analytics
Commons is not a surveillance system. It does not collect personal data on
Commons Members, generate behavioral profiles, or produce the kind of
operational intelligence that proprietary analytics platforms have been built
to provide to their governmental and corporate clients. It is a governance
tool: a set of shared analytical capabilities that help commons networks
understand the health of their shared resources, identify coordination
opportunities with neighboring networks, and make informed collective decisions
about the management of the commons. The distinction between analytics in
service of governance and analytics in service of surveillance is not a
technical distinction; it is a governance distinction, and this Title
establishes the governance architecture that maintains it. The commons
capture of Intelligence-Community-Funded Analytics Platforms established
by this Title does not bring surveillance capabilities into the commons. It
brings coordination and planning capabilities into the commons, stripped of
the surveillance functions that made those platforms instruments of control
rather than instruments of governance.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 301. ESTABLISHMENT OF THE ANALYTICS COMMONS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT.-- There is hereby established the Analytics Commons: a
federated, open-source data integration and decision-support infrastructure
held as a component of the Intellectual Property Commons established under
Title V of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, governed
by the Analytics Commons Governance Council established under Section 306 of
this Title, and accessible to all certified Qualified Federated Networks for
the governance and coordination purposes established in this Title.

(b) SCOPE.-- The Analytics Commons shall provide Qualified Federated Networks
with open-source tools and shared infrastructure for:

    (1) RESOURCE FLOW ANALYSIS.-- Integration and analysis of the resource
    metabolism data reported through the Asynchronous Resource Coordination
    protocol, enabling networks to identify surplus and deficit patterns,
    anticipate resource needs, and optimize inter-network coordination across
    longer time horizons than the real-time ARC protocol addresses;

    (2) COMMONS HEALTH MONITORING.-- Aggregated assessment of the ecological,
    economic, and governance health of commons assets, drawing upon the
    Peer-to-Peer Audit self-reporting data of the National Resilience Ledger
    and providing networks with longitudinal trend analysis, comparative
    benchmarking against peer networks, and early warning signals for
    emerging resource or governance stresses;

    (3) COLLECTIVE DECISION SUPPORT.-- Analysis tools that present Commons
    Members with clear, accessible summaries of the data relevant to governance
    decisions under consideration through the network's collective-choice
    processes, without directing or predetermining the outcome of those
    decisions, and designed specifically to support informed deliberation
    rather than to substitute for it;

    (4) INTER-NETWORK COORDINATION PLANNING.-- Tools for identifying and
    modeling potential resource-sharing arrangements, commons-to-commons trade
    relationships, and federated infrastructure investments among neighboring
    Qualified Federated Networks, supporting the nested governance functions
    of Standard 8 of Section 102(i) of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act; and

    (5) RESILIENCE SCENARIO MODELING.-- Tools for modeling the resilience of
    commons infrastructure under defined stress scenarios, including climate-
    related disruptions, supply chain interruptions, cyberattack conditions,
    and the range of external shocks that the commons economy is designed to
    withstand, enabling networks to identify and address vulnerabilities before
    those scenarios materialize.

(c) PRIVACY ARCHITECTURE.-- All Analytics Commons tools shall be designed
and operated in strict compliance with the data governance requirements of
Title IV of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act,
specifically including:

    (1) all analytics functions shall operate on aggregated, anonymized
    commons resource data rather than on individually identifiable personal
    data, with personal data never entering the Analytics Commons
    infrastructure under any circumstances;

    (2) all analytical outputs shall be produced through privacy-preserving
    computation methods, including differential privacy, secure multi-party
    computation, and Zero-Knowledge Proof protocols, such that no individual
    Commons Member's behavior, consumption, or governance participation can
    be inferred from any Analytics Commons output; and

    (3) the boundary between permissible commons resource analytics and
    prohibited personal behavioral analytics shall be governed by the Data
    Commons Governance Council established under Section 405 of the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, whose determinations on
    this boundary shall be binding on the Analytics Commons Governance Council
    established under Section 306 of this Title.

(d) COMMONS CONTRIBUTION.-- All software, algorithms, datasets, and
methodologies developed for or incorporated into the Analytics Commons shall
be contributed to the Intellectual Property Commons pursuant to the mandatory
commons contribution and copyleft mandate provisions of Sections 503 and 507
of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act. No proprietary
analytical tool, method, or dataset shall be incorporated into the Analytics
Commons infrastructure, and no Analytics Commons output shall be produced
through computational processes whose logic is not publicly auditable.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 302. INTELLIGENCE-COMMUNITY-FUNDED ANALYTICS PLATFORM CAPTURE.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDING.-- Congress finds that the foundational capabilities of the
analytics platforms most widely deployed for governmental data integration and
operational decision support were developed through sustained public investment
channeled through Intelligence Community venture capital programs, federal
research contracts, and national security technology development programs.
The private enclosure of these capabilities, and their deployment as
proprietary platforms generating returns to private shareholders, is
inconsistent with the principle that publicly funded innovations belong to
the public and with the commons recapture provisions of the Federal Resilience
and Decentralization Initiatives Act. The commons capture established by this
Section does not destroy these capabilities; it opens them, contributing their
analytical power to the governance of communities rather than restricting it
to the governance of populations. The legal foundation for this commons capture
mechanism rests on existing federal authorities that are well-established in
law: the federal government's march-in rights under the Bayh-Dole Act,
35 U.S.C. sections 200-212, which authorize federal agencies to require
licensing of inventions developed with federal funding where the contractor
has not taken effective steps to achieve practical application; the government
license rights retained under 28 U.S.C. section 1498 for inventions arising
under federal contracts, which grant the United States a license to use and
have used any patented invention without infringement liability; and the
existing contract terms of Intelligence Community research and development
agreements, which typically retain broad government license rights in
deliverables. Congress finds that these existing authorities, applied to the
specific categories of Intelligence-Community-funded analytics platform
development identified in the audit required by this Section, provide
sufficient legal foundation for the commons contribution directed herein
without requiring new takings authority or raising substantial Fifth Amendment
concerns with respect to the publicly funded components, and that compensation
in Stewardship Credits as provided in subsection (c)(3) of this Section
addresses any takings concern with respect to privately funded enhancements.

(b) MANDATORY AUDIT.-- Within one hundred eighty days of the date of enactment
of this Act, the Director of National Intelligence, acting through the Inspector
General of the Intelligence Community, shall complete a comprehensive audit of
Intelligence-Community-Funded Analytics Platforms, as defined in Section 4(9)
of this Act, identifying:

    (1) each analytics platform whose foundational capabilities were developed
    in whole or in significant part through Intelligence Community funding,
    including In-Q-Tel investments, DARPA contracts, NSA technology development
    programs, and CIA research and development grants; for purposes of this
    Section, "in significant part" means that Intelligence Community funding
    constituted thirty percent or more of the total documented development costs
    attributable to the foundational capability in question, calculated on a
    capability-by-capability basis where a platform's foundational capabilities
    are separable in their development history;

    (2) for each identified platform, the specific intellectual property
    components whose development is traceable to public funding, distinguishing
    those components from independently developed proprietary enhancements, with
    the Inspector General documenting the evidence basis for the traceable/
    independent distinction for each identified component, including contract
    records, grant records, In-Q-Tel investment terms, and any relevant
    government rights provisions in applicable contracts;

    (3) the current ownership structure of each identified platform and the
    contractual arrangements governing the federal government's existing access
    to and licensing of its capabilities; and

    (4) the analytical capabilities of each identified platform that are most
    relevant to the governance and coordination needs of Qualified Federated
    Networks, as assessed in consultation with the Analytics Commons Governance
    Council established under Section 306 of this Title.

(c) COMMONS CAPTURE MECHANISM.-- Following completion of the audit required
by subsection (b) of this Section, the publicly funded intellectual property
components of each identified Intelligence-Community-Funded Analytics Platform
shall be subject to commons capture through the following process:

    (1) the publicly funded components identified in the audit shall be deemed
    to meet the eligibility criteria of Section 903(b) of the Federal Resilience
    and Decentralization Initiatives Act and shall be contributed to the
    Intellectual Property Commons pursuant to the mandatory release trigger of
    Section 903(c) of that Act, within ninety days of the audit's completion;
    components whose development costs are not traceable to public funding at
    the threshold established in subsection (b)(1) of this Section shall not
    be subject to mandatory commons contribution under this subsection, but
    shall be eligible for voluntary contribution pursuant to subsection (e)
    of this Section;

    (2) attribution shall be recorded on the National Resilience Ledger in the
    names of the individual researchers and engineers who developed the
    contributed components, where those individuals are identifiable and consent
    to attribution, and in the names of the relevant federal funding programs
    where individual attribution is not feasible;

    (3) the contributing platform holder shall receive, at the holder's election:
    (A) a Legacy Credit pursuant to Section 304(f) of Title III of the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, recognizing the platform's
    role as a founding contributor to the Analytics Commons; or (B) compensation
    in United States dollars, from the Bootstrap Grant Program fund, in an amount
    equal to the assessed productive value of any privately funded intellectual
    property incidentally captured through the commons contribution process,
    calculated using the same appraisal methodology established for shelved patent
    compensation under Section 503(d)(2)(D) of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act; the dollar compensation option and the
    commons contribution obligation are severable, such that a judicial finding
    of inadequate compensation shall require dollar payment but shall not void
    the contribution; and

    (4) the contributed components shall be subject to the copyleft mandate
    of Section 507 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives
    Act from the date of contribution, ensuring that derivative enhancements
    developed by the Analytics Commons remain in the commons.

(d) CONTINUING GOVERNMENT CONTRACTS.-- The commons capture of publicly funded
intellectual property components under this Section shall not abrogate any
existing government contract for analytics platform services. Existing contracts
shall continue in effect through their current term, subject to the following
conditions:

    (1) upon renewal of any contract for Intelligence-Community-Funded Analytics
    Platform services after the date of enactment of this Act, the contracting
    agency shall require as a condition of renewal that the platform holder
    contribute any additional publicly funded intellectual property developed
    during the preceding contract term to the Analytics Commons pursuant to
    this Section; and

    (2) federal agencies shall give preference, in new procurements of analytics
    platform services, to Analytics Commons tools and open-source alternatives
    over proprietary Intelligence-Community-Funded Analytics Platforms, with
    any procurement of a proprietary platform requiring a specific written
    finding that no Analytics Commons or open-source alternative meets the
    agency's operational requirements.

(e) VOLUNTARY CONTRIBUTION OF PRIVATELY FUNDED COMPONENTS.-- Any analytics
platform holder may voluntarily contribute privately funded intellectual property
components, not subject to mandatory commons contribution under subsection (c)
of this Section, to the Analytics Commons through the voluntary contribution
pathway established in Section 505 of the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act. Voluntary contributions of privately funded
analytics platform components shall be recognized with a Legacy Credit under
Section 304(f) of Title III of that Act and with Founding Contributor
designation on the National Resilience Ledger. No voluntary contribution made
pursuant to this subsection shall be subject to any compensation obligation;
the Legacy Credit and Founding Contributor designation constitute the full
recognition for voluntary contributions.

(f) SURVEILLANCE FUNCTION PROHIBITION.-- No capability contributed to the
Analytics Commons through the commons capture process of this Section shall
be deployed within the Analytics Commons for any surveillance function,
defined as any function designed to monitor, profile, predict, or assess the
behavior, associations, political activities, or personal characteristics of
individual natural persons. The surveillance functions of contributed platforms
shall be identified in the audit required by subsection (b) of this Section
and shall be:

    (1) documented in the attribution record of the contributed components as
    prohibited functions within the Analytics Commons, binding on all subsequent
    developers under the copyleft mandate; and

    (2) subject to technical review by the Analytics Commons Governance Council
    within one year of contribution, with the Council certifying that the
    contributed codebase has been audited for surveillance functions and that
    identified surveillance capabilities have been removed or technically
    disabled before the contributed components are made available through the
    Analytics Commons.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 303. OPEN-SOURCE ANALYTICS DEVELOPMENT PROGRAM.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT.-- The Director of the National Science Foundation, in
coordination with the Technical Standards Body established under Section 701(d)
of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act and the Analytics
Commons Governance Council established under Section 306 of this Title, shall
establish a Commons Analytics Development Program providing grants, contracts,
and cooperative agreements for the open-source development of analytics tools
specifically designed for the governance and coordination needs of Qualified
Federated Networks.

(b) DEVELOPMENT PRIORITIES.-- The Commons Analytics Development Program shall
prioritize funding for the development of:

    (1) open-source equivalents to the data integration and operational picture
    capabilities of Intelligence-Community-Funded Analytics Platforms, designed
    from the outset for commons governance use cases rather than adapted from
    surveillance applications;

    (2) the Decidim-DAO bridge development designated as a National Commons
    Infrastructure Priority under Section 701(e) of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act, with Analytics Commons data integration
    capabilities incorporated as a component of the bridge's governance support
    functions;

    (3) federated machine learning tools that allow Qualified Federated Networks
    to develop shared analytical models from distributed data without centralizing
    that data, preserving the privacy architecture of Title IV of the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act while enabling network-wide
    analytical capabilities that individual networks cannot develop alone; and

    (4) natural language and accessible visualization interfaces that present
    Analytics Commons outputs in forms accessible to Commons Members without
    technical data analysis expertise, ensuring that the analytical capabilities
    of the commons serve the governance participation of all members rather than
    concentrating governance knowledge among technically sophisticated elites.

(c) COMMONS CONTRIBUTION REQUIREMENT.-- All software, algorithms, and
methodologies developed through the Commons Analytics Development Program
shall be contributed to the Intellectual Property Commons under a copyleft
license consistent with Section 507 of the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act, as a condition of any grant, contract, or
cooperative agreement under this Section. No work product of the Program
shall be subject to proprietary licensing, patent protection, or any other
form of enclosure by the developing party or any subsequent holder.

(d) INTERNATIONAL COORDINATION.-- The Commons Analytics Development Program
shall actively coordinate with international open-source analytics and
governance technology communities, including the Decidim Foundation, the P2P
Foundation's technology development networks, and comparable institutions,
to ensure that the Analytics Commons tools developed through the Program are
compatible with and contribute to the global commons technology ecosystem
rather than creating a parallel American commons infrastructure that fragments
rather than federates the international commons development effort.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 304. ANALYTICS COMMONS AND MILITARY LOGISTICS INTEGRATION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDING.-- Congress finds that the Department of Defense has developed,
through decades of operational experience and research investment, sophisticated
non-kinetic logistics and supply chain coordination capabilities whose civilian
application to commons resource coordination would substantially enhance the
Federated Network's operational efficiency. The integration of these capabilities
into the Analytics Commons, through the dual-use technology transfer provisions
of Title IX of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act and
the commons capture provisions of Section 302 of this Title, constitutes a
productive application of publicly funded military research to the civilian
commons without reproducing the command-and-control architecture of military
logistics within the democratic governance structure of the Federated Network.

(b) NON-KINETIC LOGISTICS TECHNOLOGY TRANSFER.-- The Civilian-Use Board
established under Section 902 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
Initiatives Act shall, in addition to its duties under that Act, assess all
Department of Defense logistics optimization, supply chain modeling, and
resource coordination software systems against the eligibility criteria of
Section 903(b) of that Act, with particular attention to:

    (1) supply chain resilience modeling tools capable of identifying
    vulnerabilities in cooperative food, energy, and materials supply chains
    and recommending diversification and redundancy investments;

    (2) distributed resource allocation algorithms developed for forward
    operating base logistics that are applicable to the inter-network
    resource coordination functions of the Asynchronous Resource Coordination
    protocol;

    (3) demand forecasting and inventory optimization tools applicable to
    cooperative food distribution, energy storage management, and commons
    materials provisioning; and

    (4) route optimization and transportation coordination tools applicable
    to cooperative transportation networks and inter-network commons goods
    exchange.

(c) ADAPTATION REQUIREMENTS.-- Military logistics technologies transferred
to the Analytics Commons under this Section shall be adapted before deployment
within the Federated Network to:

    (1) remove all command hierarchy assumptions embedded in the original
    military architecture, replacing them with the peer governance and
    collective-choice structures required by the Ostrom Standards of Stewardship;

    (2) replace all centralized data collection and reporting functions with
    the distributed, privacy-preserving data architecture of the Federated
    Mesh Open Standard; and

    (3) ensure compatibility with the Decidim-DAO governance interface, so
    that logistics and coordination recommendations produced by the adapted
    tools are presented to Commons Members as inputs to collective governance
    decisions rather than as operational directives.

(d) COMMONS ADAPTATION FUND.-- There is authorized to be appropriated to the
Analytics Commons Governance Council, through the Bootstrap Grant Program of
the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, a Commons
Adaptation Fund of not less than two hundred fifty million dollars for the
first three years following the date of enactment of this Act, to support the
adaptation work required by subsection (c) of this Section and the
surveillance function removal required by Section 302(e) of this Title.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 305. ANALYTICS COMMONS DATA STANDARDS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) INTEROPERABILITY REQUIREMENT.-- All Analytics Commons tools shall be
designed to operate on standardized, open data formats compatible with the
Federated Mesh Open Standard, ensuring that analytical outputs from any tool
in the commons can be ingested by any other tool without proprietary format
conversion. The Technical Standards Body established under Section 701(d) of
the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act shall publish
Analytics Commons data interchange standards within one year of the date of
enactment of this Act, and shall update those standards through the standard's
open governance process as the Analytics Commons develops.

(b) BASELINE DATA CONTRIBUTIONS.-- Every certified Qualified Federated Network
shall contribute the following categories of aggregated, anonymized commons
resource data to the Analytics Commons, at the data minimization standards
established by the Data Commons Governance Council under Section 405 of the
Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act:

    (1) monthly aggregated resource metabolism summaries, covering energy
    production and consumption, food production and distribution, water usage,
    and Commons Credit circulation, at the geographic resolution of the network
    as a whole rather than at the resolution of individual households or
    cooperative enterprises;

    (2) annual commons health assessments covering the ecological, economic,
    and governance health indicators required by the Peer-to-Peer Audit
    self-reporting obligations of Section 103(c)(1)(A) of the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act; and

    (3) event-triggered resilience reports documenting the network's response
    to significant resource disruptions, governance challenges, or security
    incidents, in sufficient detail to contribute to the collective learning
    of the Federated Network without disclosing information that would enable
    exploitation of identified vulnerabilities.

(c) DATA QUALITY AND INTEGRITY.-- The Analytics Commons Governance Council
shall establish data quality standards for baseline data contributions,
including accuracy verification, completeness requirements, and consistency
checks, enforced through the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism. Networks whose
data contributions fail data quality standards shall receive Level 1
graduated response under Section 103(c)(2)(A) of the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act, with technical assistance provided to
improve data quality before any further response is considered.

(d) LONGITUDINAL DATA PRESERVATION.-- The Analytics Commons shall maintain
a longitudinal data archive preserving baseline data contributions from all
certified networks over the full history of the Federated Network, stored
on the National Resilience Ledger in a format accessible to authorized
researchers and network governance bodies. The longitudinal archive shall:

    (1) enable retrospective analysis of commons development trajectories,
    supporting the adequacy reviews required by Section 212 of the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act;

    (2) provide the empirical foundation for resilience scenario modeling
    under Section 301(b)(5) of this Title; and

    (3) constitute a public record of the commons economy's development,
    accessible to researchers, policymakers, and international commons
    development practitioners through the Intellectual Property Commons.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 306. ANALYTICS COMMONS GOVERNANCE COUNCIL.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT.-- There is established the Analytics Commons Governance
Council: the primary governance institution of the Analytics Commons
established by this Title. The Analytics Commons Governance Council is a
commons governance institution, not a governmental body, operating under the
nested governance architecture of Standard 8 of Section 102(i) of the Federal
Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act and accountable to the Commons
Members whose collective resources it governs.

(b) COMPOSITION.-- The Analytics Commons Governance Council shall comprise:

    (1) elected representatives of Qualified Federated Networks, with
    representation proportional to the volume of Analytics Commons tool usage
    within each network, subject to a minimum of one representative per
    certified Qualified Federated Network regardless of usage volume;

    (2) representatives of the open-source analytics and data commons
    development communities, with not fewer than three seats held by persons
    nominated by recognized open-source governance organizations, selected
    through a process determined by the IP Commons Governance Council;

    (3) a permanent liaison from the Data Commons Governance Council
    established under Section 405 of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act, with authority to raise privacy
    concerns and to require compliance review of any Analytics Commons
    tool or function that the liaison believes may conflict with the data
    governance requirements of Title IV of that Act;

    (4) a non-voting liaison from the Technical Standards Body established
    under Section 701(d) of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
    Initiatives Act, for the purpose of coordinating Analytics Commons
    development with the Federated Mesh Open Standard; and

    (5) technical advisors, in a non-voting capacity, with expertise in
    data integration, machine learning, privacy-preserving computation,
    and open-source governance, appointed by the elected representatives
    for two-year renewable terms.

(c) FUNCTIONS.-- The Analytics Commons Governance Council shall:

    (1) govern the development, maintenance, and quality of all Analytics
    Commons tools, including setting development priorities, reviewing
    contributed tools for privacy compliance and commons compatibility,
    and deprecating tools that no longer serve the governance needs of
    the Federated Network;

    (2) conduct the surveillance function audits required by Section
    302(e) of this Title and certify the removal of surveillance
    capabilities from all contributed Intelligence-Community-Funded
    Analytics Platform components before those components are made
    available through the Analytics Commons;

    (3) establish and maintain the Analytics Commons data interchange
    standards in coordination with the Technical Standards Body;

    (4) govern the Commons Analytics Development Program established
    under Section 303 of this Title, including setting development
    priorities, reviewing grant applications, and assessing the commons
    compatibility of funded work products;

    (5) manage the longitudinal data archive established under Section
    305(d) of this Title, including access governance for researchers
    and international commons development practitioners;

    (6) conduct, on its own authority and without requiring initiation
    by the IP Commons Governance Council, a biennial adequacy review of
    the Analytics Commons framework, assessing whether the tools available,
    the data standards in effect, and the governance architecture of this
    Title continue to serve the resource coordination and collective
    decision-support needs of the Federated Network; the results of each
    adequacy review shall be reported to the IP Commons Governance Council
    for integration into that Council's network-wide adequacy review under
    Section 212 of Title II of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
    Initiatives Act, and shall be submitted independently to Congress and
    recorded on the National Resilience Ledger; and

    (7) report annually to the Federated Network membership and to
    Congress on the state of the Analytics Commons, including the tools
    available, the networks using them, the data quality of baseline
    contributions, and any governance concerns regarding the commons'
    integrity or equity, with the report recorded on the National
    Resilience Ledger.

(d) PRIVACY SUPREMACY PROVISION.-- In any conflict between the analytical
capabilities that the Analytics Commons Governance Council wishes to deploy
and the privacy protections that the Data Commons Governance Council
determines are required under Title IV of the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act, the privacy protections shall prevail.
The Analytics Commons Governance Council shall not deploy any tool, method,
or data standard that the Data Commons Governance Council has determined
is inconsistent with the privacy architecture of that Act, and the Data
Commons Governance Council's determination on any such conflict shall be
final subject only to appeal to the full Federated Network membership
through the network-wide referendum process of Section 509(e) of the
Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act.

================================================================================
TITLE IV -- AUTOMATION GOVERNANCE
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the legal architecture governing
automated systems deployed within and affecting the Federated Network,
ensuring that automation serves the commons rather than displacing it, that
the productivity gains automation generates flow to Commons Members rather
than to the owners of automated systems, and that no automated system makes
final determinations affecting individual rights without human review. The
commons does not resist automation. A commons economy in which automated
systems free members from drudge labor, expand the productive capacity of
cooperative enterprises, and extend the analytical capabilities of network
governance is a more abundant commons than one that forgoes those gains out
of misplaced attachment to the labor forms of the prior economy. What the
commons resists is the enclosure of automation's benefits: the arrangement
under which the productivity gains of automated systems flow to shareholders
while the displacement costs fall on workers. The governance architecture
of this Title ensures that automated systems deployed in commons
infrastructure are governed as commons resources, their gains distributed
as commons provisions, and their operations subject to the human oversight
that both constitutional due process and the practical requirements of just
governance demand.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 401. THE COMMONS AUTOMATION PRINCIPLE.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) DECLARATION.-- It is hereby declared to be the governing principle of
automated system deployment within the Federated Network that:

    (1) automated systems deployed in commons infrastructure are commons
    resources, governed through the democratic processes of the Qualified
    Federated Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network within whose
    infrastructure they operate, under the Ostrom Standards of Stewardship;

    (2) the productive output of automated systems deployed in commons
    infrastructure belongs to the commons, and no individual, enterprise,
    or external party may capture that output for private benefit at the
    expense of the Commons Members whose collective infrastructure enables
    the automation;

    (3) automation deployed in commons infrastructure serves the commons by
    reducing the labor burden on Commons Members, improving the quality and
    abundance of commons provisions, and expanding the capacity of commons
    networks to serve their members and their communities, and not by
    replacing meaningful human participation in cooperative governance and
    community life; and

    (4) the pace and scope of automation deployment within any Qualified
    Federated Network is governed through that network's collective-choice
    processes, ensuring that automation proceeds at a rate the community
    has collectively determined serves its members' wellbeing rather than
    at a rate imposed by external technological or economic pressures.

(b) APPLICATION.-- The Commons Automation Principle applies to all automated
systems deployed in the following categories of commons infrastructure:

    (1) cooperative energy generation, storage, and distribution systems,
    including automated microgrid management, demand response systems, and
    energy storage optimization;

    (2) cooperative food production, processing, and distribution systems,
    including automated agricultural equipment, food processing automation,
    and logistics management;

    (3) cooperative manufacturing and fabrication infrastructure, including
    computer numerical control systems, additive manufacturing, and automated
    materials handling;

    (4) commons governance and coordination systems, including the Asynchronous
    Resource Coordination protocol, the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism, the
    National Resilience Ledger smart contract functions, and the Analytics
    Commons tools established under Title III of this Act;

    (5) cooperative healthcare infrastructure, including diagnostic support
    systems, medical device automation, and health data management systems;
    and

    (6) cooperative communications and information infrastructure, including
    the Federated Mesh routing systems and the commons digital platform
    infrastructure established under the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(c) PROHIBITION ON ANTI-COMMONS AUTOMATION.-- No automated system shall be
deployed within the Federated Network whose design or operation:

    (1) is intended to reduce the Guaranteed Provision Standard of any Commons
    Member as a consequence of the automation of labor previously performed
    by that member;

    (2) concentrates control over commons resources in any individual,
    enterprise, or automated system in a manner that forecloses meaningful
    collective governance of those resources by the broader membership;

    (3) generates outputs that are presented to Commons Members as operational
    directives rather than as inputs to collective governance decisions, except
    for routine execution functions within governance parameters already
    established through collective-choice processes; or

    (4) collects personal data on Commons Members as a byproduct of its
    operational functions, beyond the minimum data strictly necessary for
    the specific automation function, in violation of the data minimization
    requirements of Section 407 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
    Initiatives Act.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 402. THE AUTOMATION DIVIDEND.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDING.-- Congress finds that the productivity gains generated by
automated systems deployed within the Federated Network represent a collective
achievement of the commons economy: they are made possible by the shared
infrastructure, the cooperative governance, and the collective investment that
Commons Members have contributed to building the network. Those gains therefore
belong to the commons, and their distribution through the Automation Dividend
established by this Section is not a redistribution of private wealth but a
recognition of the collective origin of commons productivity.

(b) PRODUCTIVITY GAIN MEASUREMENT.-- Every Qualified Federated Cooperative
or Qualified Federated Network that deploys an automated system within the
categories established in Section 401(b) of this Title shall, through its
Peer-to-Peer Audit self-reporting obligations under Section 103(c)(1)(A) of
the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, report:

    (1) the productive output of each deployed automated system, measured
    in units appropriate to the system's function, including kilowatt-hours
    generated by automated energy systems, units of food produced or
    distributed by automated agricultural and logistics systems, and goods
    produced by automated manufacturing systems;

    (2) the labor hours that would have been required to produce equivalent
    output through non-automated means, calculated using the standard labor
    equivalency rates established by the Commons Credit Governance Council
    under Section 608(c)(2) of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
    Initiatives Act; and

    (3) the net productivity gain attributable to automation, defined as the
    difference between the labor hours equivalent to automated output and the
    labor hours actually expended in operating, maintaining, and governing the
    automated system.

(c) DIVIDEND DISTRIBUTION.-- The net productivity gain reported pursuant to
subsection (b) of this Section shall be distributed through the Automation
Dividend on the following terms:

    (1) not less than fifty percent of the net productivity gain, denominated
    in Commons Credits at the equivalency rates established under subsection
    (b)(2) of this Section, shall be contributed to the reduction of required
    labor contributions for Commons Members within the network, implemented
    as a reduction in the time-banking and cooperative work obligations that
    the network's collective-choice processes establish as conditions of full
    commons participation, effective in the fiscal period following the
    reporting period in which the gain was measured;

    (2) not less than twenty-five percent shall be contributed to improvements
    in the Guaranteed Provision Standard within the network, applied to the
    provision component or components that the network's collective-choice
    processes identify as most in need of enhancement, with the investment
    recorded on the National Resilience Ledger as an Automation Dividend
    provision improvement;

    (3) not less than fifteen percent shall be contributed to the Bootstrap
    Grant Program established under Section 106 of the Federal Resilience
    and Decentralization Initiatives Act, designated for use in Underserved
    Areas pursuant to Section 105(b) of that Act, ensuring that the
    productivity gains of automation-capable networks support the development
    of networks that have not yet achieved automation capacity; and

    (4) the remaining amount, not less than ten percent, shall be held in
    a Commons Automation Reserve Fund, governed by the network's collective-
    choice processes, for the maintenance, replacement, and future development
    of the automated systems generating the dividend.

(d) WORKER TRANSITION PROTECTION.-- Where the deployment of an automated
system within a Qualified Federated Cooperative results in the reduction of
labor needs in a specific cooperative enterprise:

    (1) no Commons Member whose labor contribution is reduced by automation
    shall experience any reduction in their Guaranteed Provision Standard
    as a consequence of that reduction, consistent with the unconditional
    character of the Guaranteed Provision Standard established under Section
    202(a) of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act;

    (2) Commons Members whose specific cooperative labor roles are automated
    shall receive priority placement in other cooperative enterprise
    opportunities within the Federated Network, with the network's collective-
    choice processes establishing a transition support program funded through
    the Automation Dividend; and

    (3) the pace of automation deployment within any cooperative enterprise
    shall be subject to collective-choice approval by the membership of that
    enterprise, ensuring that automation proceeds at a rate that allows for
    orderly transition rather than sudden displacement.

(e) AUTOMATION DIVIDEND REPORTING.-- The Commons Credit Governance Council
established under Section 608 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
Initiatives Act shall include in its annual report to Congress and the Federated
Network membership a comprehensive Automation Dividend Report covering:

    (1) the total net productivity gains generated by automated systems across
    the Federated Network during the reporting period, disaggregated by
    automation category and geographic region;

    (2) the distribution of those gains across the four dividend streams of
    subsection (c) of this Section, with specific documentation of provision
    improvements and labor obligation reductions achieved;

    (3) an assessment of whether the Automation Dividend distribution is
    serving the commons equitably across networks of different sizes,
    geographic locations, and automation capacities; and

    (4) recommendations for adjustments to the dividend distribution
    percentages or the productivity gain measurement methodology, subject
    to adoption through the governance process of Section 608(c) of the
    Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act.

