SEC. 403. THE OPEN-SOURCE AUTOMATION MANDATE.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) REQUIREMENT.-- All automated systems deployed in the categories established
in Section 401(b) of this Title, within any certified Qualified Federated
Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network, shall comply with the Open-Source
Automation Mandate, meaning:

    (1) the source code, training data, model weights, and operational
    parameters of the automated system shall be published under a copyleft
    open-source license consistent with Section 507 of the Federal Resilience
    and Decentralization Initiatives Act, and made accessible through the
    Intellectual Property Commons;

    (2) the automated system's decision logic, including the rules, thresholds,
    and optimization objectives governing its outputs, shall be documented in
    plain language accessible to non-technical Commons Members and published
    on the National Resilience Ledger alongside the system's technical
    documentation;

    (3) the automated system shall be auditable by the network's Peer-to-Peer
    Audit mechanism, providing verifiable outputs that can be cross-validated
    against physical measurements through the Federated Mesh Open Standard;
    and

    (4) any modification to the automated system's source code, training data,
    or operational parameters shall be recorded on the National Resilience
    Ledger and shall require collective-choice approval by the governing
    Qualified Federated Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network before
    deployment, except for routine maintenance updates that do not alter the
    system's decision logic or optimization objectives.

(b) COMPLIANCE TIMELINE.-- Automated systems already deployed within Qualified
Federated Networks at the time of enactment of this Act shall achieve
compliance with the Open-Source Automation Mandate on the following schedule:

    (1) within one year of enactment, for systems governing energy generation,
    distribution, or storage infrastructure;

    (2) within two years of enactment, for systems governing food production,
    processing, or distribution infrastructure;

    (3) within three years of enactment, for systems governing commons
    governance, coordination, and analytics functions; and

    (4) within four years of enactment, for all other automated systems within
    the scope of Section 401(b) of this Title.

(c) TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE.-- The Technical Standards Body established under
Section 701(d) of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act
shall provide technical assistance to Qualified Federated Networks in achieving
Open-Source Automation Mandate compliance, including:

    (1) model open-source licensing templates and documentation standards
    for each category of commons automation;

    (2) technical guidance on the auditability requirements of subsection
    (a)(3) of this Section, including specifications for the data formats
    and interface standards that enable Peer-to-Peer Audit cross-validation
    of automated system outputs; and

    (3) Bootstrap Grant funding designated for Open-Source Automation Mandate
    compliance costs, available through the Coverage Extension Grant stream
    of Section 106(b)(4) of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
    Initiatives Act.

(d) THIRD-PARTY AUTOMATION.-- Where a Qualified Federated Network operates
automated systems developed by third-party vendors rather than by the network
itself, the network shall:

    (1) require as a condition of any procurement or licensing agreement that
    the vendor comply with the Open-Source Automation Mandate with respect to
    the system's deployment within the network, contributing the relevant
    source code and documentation to the Intellectual Property Commons as
    a condition of the agreement; and

    (2) include a specific provision in any such agreement requiring the vendor
    to contribute any improvements or modifications to the system developed
    during the term of the agreement to the Intellectual Property Commons
    under the copyleft license, consistent with the commons reinvestment
    obligations of Section 307(d)(3) of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(e) NON-COMPLIANCE CONSEQUENCES.-- A Qualified Federated Network that deploys
or continues to operate an automated system not in compliance with the Open-
Source Automation Mandate after the applicable deadline established in
subsection (b) of this Section shall be subject to Level 1 graduated response
under Section 103(c)(2)(A) of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
Initiatives Act for the period of non-compliance, escalating to Level 2 if
compliance is not achieved within ninety days of the Level 1 notice.

