SEC. 404. ALGORITHMIC GOVERNANCE PROHIBITION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ABSOLUTE PROHIBITION.-- No automated system, algorithm, machine learning
model, or artificial intelligence application deployed within or affecting
the Federated Network shall make or constitute the final determination of
any matter that materially affects the rights, provisions, standing, or
obligations of any individual Commons Member, without human review and
authorization through the Human-in-the-Loop Layer established under Section
803 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(b) SCOPE.-- The prohibition established by subsection (a) of this Section
applies to all of the following categories of determination, without exception:

    (1) any determination affecting a Commons Member's entitlement to any
    component of the Guaranteed Provision Standard;

    (2) any determination affecting a Commons Member's governance rights
    within any Qualified Federated Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network;

    (3) any determination affecting a Commons Member's certification status,
    attribution registrations, or Commons Credit balance;

    (4) any determination made through the Accountability Coordination DAO
    or the transformative justice processes of the Human Reclamation and
    Community Restorative Act, consistent with the prohibition on algorithmic
    justice determinations established in Section 206(c) of that Act;

    (5) any determination by any federal agency affecting the rights or
    benefits of any individual, where that determination is substantially
    generated by an automated system without independent human review on the
    merits; and

    (6) any military targeting determination involving the potential use of
    lethal force against any specific individual, consistent with the
    requirements of international humanitarian law and the laws of armed
    conflict, which require human judgment as a matter of legal obligation
    as well as constitutional due process.

(c) AUTOMATED RECOMMENDATIONS DISTINGUISHED.-- The prohibition established
by subsection (a) of this Section does not prohibit automated systems from
generating recommendations, analyses, flags, or supporting information that
human decision-makers consider in reaching a determination. The prohibition
applies to the final determination, not to the inputs that inform it. The
distinction between a prohibited automated final determination and a
permissible automated recommendation is:

    (1) a determination is automated and prohibited where the human reviewer
    lacks meaningful access to the evidence and reasoning underlying the
    automated output and cannot independently assess its accuracy and fairness;

    (2) a determination is automated and prohibited where the practical effect
    of the human review is rubber-stamping of the automated output due to
    volume, time pressure, or information asymmetry, regardless of the formal
    availability of human override; and

    (3) a recommendation is permissible where the human reviewer has full
    access to the underlying evidence, has genuine capacity and time to assess
    the recommendation independently, and retains real authority to reach a
    different conclusion without institutional pressure toward conformity with
    the automated output.

(d) AUTOMATION BIAS TRAINING.-- Consistent with the automation bias training
requirements of Section 803(d)(4) of the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act, all human reviewers exercising oversight
of automated systems under this Section shall receive training that:

    (1) explicitly addresses the empirical literature on automation bias,
    including the documented tendency of human reviewers to defer to automated
    outputs even when those outputs are demonstrably incorrect;

    (2) provides practical exercises in identifying cases where automated
    systems have produced outputs inconsistent with the facts of specific
    situations; and

    (3) establishes institutional review processes in which the rate of human
    override of automated recommendations is tracked and reported, with
    anomalously low override rates treated as an indicator of potential
    automation bias requiring investigation rather than as evidence of
    automated system accuracy.

(e) FEDERAL AGENCY COMPLIANCE.-- All federal agencies that deploy automated
decision-making systems affecting the rights or benefits of individuals shall,
within two years of the date of enactment of this Act:

    (1) audit all deployed automated decision systems against the prohibition
    established by subsection (a) of this Section, identifying any system
    that is making or effectively making final determinations without adequate
    human review;

    (2) remediate all identified violations by establishing genuine human
    review processes meeting the standards of subsection (c) of this Section;
    and

    (3) report the results of the audit and the remediation actions taken to
    Congress, with the report made publicly available through the National
    Resilience Ledger.

