SEC. 405. AUTOMATION AND CREATIVE LABOR.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDING.-- Congress finds that the application of automated systems to
creative work -- including the generation of literary, musical, visual, and
other artistic output through artificial intelligence -- raises specific
governance questions that the Commons Automation Principle and the IP Commons
attribution framework of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
Initiatives Act address together, but that warrant specific acknowledgment
in the context of this Title's broader automation governance architecture.
Creative labor is not merely a category of productive activity; it is a
primary domain of human meaning-making, and the governance of automation
in this domain requires particular care to ensure that automated creative
tools serve human creative expression rather than displacing it as the
primary source of cultural life within the commons.

(b) CREATIVE AUTOMATION PRINCIPLES.-- Automated systems deployed within the
Federated Network for creative assistance, content generation, or cultural
production shall be governed by the following principles, supplementing the
attribution rules of Section 510 of the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act:

    (1) automated creative tools shall be designed and deployed as instruments
    that expand the creative capacity of Commons Members rather than as
    substitutes for human creative participation in commons cultural life;

    (2) the deployment of automated creative tools within a Qualified Federated
    Network shall be subject to collective-choice governance by the network's
    membership, which shall determine the appropriate role of automated
    creative assistance in the network's cultural programming, educational
    activities, and community expression;

    (3) no automated creative system shall be presented to Commons Members as
    a human creator or as the product of human creative labor without
    disclosure of its automated origin, consistent with the attribution
    transparency requirements of Section 504 of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act; and

    (4) the productivity gains of automated creative tools deployed within
    commons cultural institutions -- including reduced costs of content
    production, expanded creative output, and enhanced accessibility of
    cultural participation -- shall be distributed through the Automation
    Dividend mechanism of Section 402 of this Title, with particular attention
    to directing a portion of those gains toward supporting human creative
    practitioners whose labor may be reduced by creative automation.

(c) AI TRAINING DATA AND COMMONS ATTRIBUTION.-- Consistent with Section 510(b)
(3) of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, automated
systems trained on works contributed to the Intellectual Property Commons shall:

    (1) maintain records of the commons training data used in their development,
    with those records accessible to the Analytics Commons for the purpose
    of calculating the collective attribution contributions that commons works
    make to AI system capabilities;

    (2) contribute to the commons general fund, through a mechanism established
    by the IP Commons Governance Council, a portion of the Automation Dividend
    generated by their deployment, in recognition of the collective intellectual
    contribution that commons training data represents; and

    (3) be subject to the copyleft mandate of Section 507 of the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act with respect to any creative
    outputs that are substantially derived from commons training data, ensuring
    that the commons contribution to AI creative capability is reciprocated
    through contribution back to the commons.

