SEC. 406. AUTOMATION GOVERNANCE COUNCIL.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT.-- There is established the Automation Governance Council:
a commons governance institution responsible for the ongoing governance of
automated systems deployed within the Federated Network, operating under the
nested governance architecture of Standard 8 of Section 102(i) of the Federal
Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act and accountable to the Commons
Members whose cooperative infrastructure the automation serves.

(b) COMPOSITION.-- The Automation Governance Council shall comprise:

    (1) elected representatives of Qualified Federated Networks, with
    representation proportional to the volume of automated system deployments
    within each network, subject to a minimum of one representative per
    certified Qualified Federated Network;

    (2) worker representatives from cooperative enterprises operating automated
    systems within the Federated Network, with not fewer than five seats held
    by persons nominated by labor cooperative governance bodies, ensuring
    that the perspectives of workers whose labor is most directly affected
    by automation deployment are represented in its governance;

    (3) a permanent liaison from the IP Commons Governance Council established
    under Section 509 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
    Initiatives Act, for the purpose of coordinating automation governance
    with the AI-generated works attribution framework of Section 510 of
    that Act;

    (4) a permanent liaison from the Analytics Commons Governance Council
    established under Section 306 of this Title, for the purpose of
    coordinating automation governance with the analytics infrastructure
    that monitoring automated system performance requires; and

    (5) technical advisors, in a non-voting capacity, with expertise in
    automated systems, artificial intelligence, labor economics, and
    cooperative governance, appointed by the elected representatives for
    two-year renewable terms, with the Platform Cooperativism Consortium
    invited to nominate a standing technical advisor for matters relating to
    the cooperative governance of digital platforms and algorithmic systems;
    the nomination is advisory and the elected representatives retain full
    discretion over the appointment.

(c) FUNCTIONS.-- The Automation Governance Council shall:

    (1) monitor compliance with the Open-Source Automation Mandate established
    under Section 403 of this Title, in coordination with the Peer-to-Peer
    Audit mechanism, and recommend graduated response actions to the Office
    of Federated Stewardship or, following the network maturity threshold,
    to the network's self-governance bodies for non-compliant deployments;

    (2) govern the Automation Dividend measurement methodology and distribution
    standards established under Section 402 of this Title, in coordination
    with the Commons Credit Governance Council, updating those standards through
    open deliberative process as the commons economy's automation capacity
    develops;

    (3) assess the impact of automation deployment on labor contribution
    patterns across the Federated Network, identifying categories of commons
    work being displaced by automation and recommending transition support
    measures through the Automation Dividend worker transition provisions of
    Section 402(d) of this Title;

    (4) establish and maintain commons standards for automated system safety,
    reliability, and fail-safe behavior, applicable to all automated systems
    deployed in commons-critical infrastructure, with particular attention
    to ensuring that automated system failures activate the Local Resilience
    Mode protocols of Section 704(b) of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act rather than cascading through interconnected
    commons infrastructure;

    (5) conduct the federal agency compliance review established under Section
    404(e) of this Title, providing technical assistance to agencies seeking
    to remediate automated governance violations;

    (6) conduct, on its own authority and without requiring initiation by the
    IP Commons Governance Council, a biennial adequacy review of the automation
    governance framework, assessing whether the Open-Source Automation Mandate,
    the Automation Dividend distribution standards, and the Algorithmic
    Governance Prohibition continue to serve the commons values of this Title
    in light of developments in automated systems technology and commons economy
    practice; the results of each adequacy review shall be reported to the IP
    Commons Governance Council for integration into that Council's network-wide
    adequacy review, and shall be submitted independently to Congress and recorded
    on the National Resilience Ledger; and

    (7) report annually to the Federated Network membership and to Congress
    on the state of automation within the commons economy, including the
    Automation Dividend Report required by Section 402(e) of this Title,
    an assessment of Open-Source Automation Mandate compliance, and
    recommendations for legislative or governance adjustments in response
    to emerging automation developments.

(d) RELATIONSHIP TO HUMAN-IN-THE-LOOP LAYER.-- The Automation Governance
Council shall work in close coordination with the Human Review Panel
infrastructure of the Human-in-the-Loop Layer established under Section 803
of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, including by:

    (1) providing training materials on the specific automated systems deployed
    within each Qualified Federated Network to Human Review Panel members,
    ensuring that reviewers understand the logic, limitations, and known
    failure modes of the systems whose outputs they review; and

    (2) analyzing patterns in Human Review Panel override rates across the
    network to identify automated systems that are generating systematically
    flawed outputs, escalating to Open-Source Automation Mandate compliance
    review where override patterns suggest fundamental design problems.

