TITLE V -- ADMINISTRATIVE AND JUDICIAL PROVISIONS
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the administrative framework,
judicial review mechanisms, dependency provisions, conforming amendments to
existing federal law, and appropriations authorities necessary to make the
preceding Titles of this Act operative and durable. As with the equivalent
provisions of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act and
the Human Reclamation and Community Restorative Act, this Title does not create
new substantive rights or obligations. It provides the legal infrastructure
through which the rights and obligations established in Titles I through IV
are administered, enforced, integrated into the existing body of federal law,
and protected against the administrative erosion and executive reinterpretation
that commonly attenuate the effect of reform legislation between sessions of
Congress. The provisions of this Title are drafted with particular attention
to the specific vulnerabilities of defense posture and automation governance
legislation: the tendency of executive branch actors to reinterpret national
security mandates in ways that restore the postures Congress has directed them
to change, and the tendency of administrative agencies to treat algorithmic
governance prohibitions as aspirational rather than binding. Both tendencies
are directly addressed in this Title.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 501. DEPENDENCY ON THE FRDI ACT AND HRCR ACT.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) STRUCTURAL DEPENDENCY.-- The defense posture reorientation, commons network
security, analytics commons, and automation governance provisions of this Act
are structurally dependent upon the material and social commons infrastructure
established by the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act and
the Human Reclamation and Community Restorative Act. Specifically:

    (1) the force structure transition of Title I of this Act is strategically
    coherent only as the domestic commons infrastructure of the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act matures, reducing the
    material dependence on petrodollar arrangements that the prior defense
    posture protected, and the transition timelines of Section 103 of Title I
    are calibrated accordingly;

    (2) the commons network security provisions of Title II of this Act
    presuppose the existence of certified Qualified Federated Networks operating
    under the Ostrom Standards of Stewardship established by the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, and the security
    architecture of Title II functions through the distributed governance
    mechanisms of that Act rather than through independent administrative
    infrastructure;

    (3) the Analytics Commons of Title III of this Act is a component of the
    Intellectual Property Commons established by the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act, governed through the commons governance
    institutions of that Act, and its operation depends upon the data
    governance architecture, the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism, and the National
    Resilience Ledger infrastructure of that Act being in place; and

    (4) the automation governance provisions of Title IV of this Act operate
    through and reinforce the Human-in-the-Loop Layer, the Open-Source mandate,
    and the commons credit architecture of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act, and independently through the
    transformative justice prohibitions on algorithmic governance in the Human
    Reclamation and Community Restorative Act.

(b) TRIGGERING CONDITIONS.-- The following provisions of this Act shall not
take operative effect in any geographic area or institutional context until
the specified triggering conditions are met:

    (1) the Commons Infrastructure Defense Program of Section 102(c) of Title
    I of this Act shall not extend support to any Qualified Federated Network
    until that network has achieved certification pursuant to Title I of the
    Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act;

    (2) the Analytics Commons tools of Title III of this Act shall not be
    deployed within any network until that network's compliance with the data
    governance requirements of Title IV of the Federal Resilience and
    Decentralization Initiatives Act has been verified through the Peer-to-Peer
    Audit mechanism; and

    (3) the Automation Dividend distribution mechanism of Section 402 of Title
    IV of this Act shall not be operative within any network until that network
    has established the Commons Credit infrastructure required for dividend
    denomination and distribution pursuant to Title VI of the Federal
    Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(c) FEDERAL BACKSTOP.-- Where the triggering conditions of subsection (b)
of this Section have not been met in a geographic area affected by the defense
posture transition of Title I of this Act, the federal government shall:

    (1) accelerate the Bootstrap Grant and coverage extension provisions of
    Sections 105 and 106 of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization
    Initiatives Act for that area, treating the absence of a receiving commons
    network as a coverage gap of the highest security priority; and

    (2) ensure that any defense savings realized through the force structure
    transition of Section 103 of Title I of this Act that are attributable to
    reduced commitments in areas without established commons networks are
    directed specifically toward the Bootstrap Grant Program for those areas,
    accelerating the commons development that makes the transition strategically
    coherent.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 502. EXECUTIVE BRANCH COMPLIANCE MECHANISMS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) NON-REINTERPRETATION PROVISION.-- The defense posture declaration of
Section 101 of Title I of this Act and the missions no longer constituting
primary defense policy under Section 101(b) of that Title are statutory
directives to the Executive Branch, not grants of discretion to the Executive
Branch to determine what those provisions mean. Specifically:

    (1) no executive order, presidential directive, national security
    memorandum, or administrative guidance shall be issued that reinterprets
    the missions no longer constituting primary defense policy under Section
    101(b) of Title I of this Act in a manner that restores those missions
    as primary defense commitments under different terminology or framing;

    (2) any executive order or presidential directive that purports to authorize
    defense commitments inconsistent with the Resilience-Based Defense Posture
    declared in Section 101(a) of Title I of this Act shall be subject to
    immediate judicial review under the standard established in Section 505(c)
    of this Title upon the application of any member of Congress or any
    certified Qualified Federated Network; and

    (3) the Secretary of Defense shall include in each annual defense posture
    report to Congress a specific certification that the defense activities of
    the preceding year were consistent with the Resilience-Based Defense
    Posture declaration, with any inconsistencies identified and explained.

(b) ALGORITHMIC GOVERNANCE PROHIBITION ENFORCEMENT.-- The prohibition on
automated final determinations established in Section 404 of Title IV of this
Act shall be enforced against federal agencies through the following mechanisms,
supplementing the agency compliance audit required by Section 404(e) of that
Title:

    (1) the Office of Management and Budget shall issue guidance to all federal
    agencies within one year of the date of enactment of this Act establishing
    the standards for human review processes that satisfy Section 404(c) of
    Title IV of this Act, with particular attention to the rubber-stamping
    prohibition of Section 404(c)(2) of that Title;

    (2) the Government Accountability Office shall conduct biennial audits of
    federal agency automated decision systems, assessing compliance with Section
    404 of Title IV of this Act and reporting findings to Congress with
    recommendations for remediation; and

    (3) any individual whose rights or benefits are materially affected by an
    automated federal agency determination that violates Section 404 of Title
    IV of this Act shall have a private right of action in any federal district
    court of competent jurisdiction, with the agency bearing the burden of
    demonstrating that the determination was made through a human review process
    meeting the standards of Section 404(c) of that Title.

(c) INTELLIGENCE REFORM COMPLIANCE.-- The mass surveillance termination and
covert interference prohibition provisions of Section 104 of Title I of this
Act shall be enforced through the following mechanisms, supplementing the
Inspector General oversight established by that Section:

    (1) any officer or employee of the Intelligence Community who in good faith
    reports to the congressional intelligence committees, the Inspector General
    of the Intelligence Community, or the Privacy and Civil Liberties Oversight
    Board that an Intelligence Community program is operating in violation of
    Section 104(b) or Section 104(c) of Title I of this Act shall be entitled
    to the full protections of the Intelligence Community Whistleblower
    Protection Act of 1998 and shall not be subject to any adverse personnel
    action, security clearance revocation, or prosecution arising solely from
    that disclosure; and

    (2) the Privacy and Civil Liberties Oversight Board shall conduct an annual
    review of Intelligence Community compliance with Section 104 of Title I
    of this Act, with a public report submitted to Congress and recorded on
    the National Resilience Ledger.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 503. CONSTITUTIONAL SAFE HARBOR.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Any federal officer, employee, or agent who in good faith takes any action to
implement the provisions of this Act, including actions that result in the
reorientation of defense posture, the termination of mass surveillance programs,
the contribution of Intelligence-Community-Funded Analytics Platform components
to the Analytics Commons, the removal of automated final determination systems
from federal agency operations, or the reduction of executive authority over
the Federated Network consistent with the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act, shall not be subject to civil or criminal
liability under any federal or state law arising solely from the performance
of those implementation duties, on terms equivalent to the Constitutional Safe
Harbor established under Section 1101 of the Federal Resilience and
Decentralization Initiatives Act. This safe harbor is retroactive to the date
of introduction of this Act in Congress.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 504. SEVERABILITY.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) GENERAL SEVERABILITY.-- If any provision of this Act, or the application
of any provision to any person or circumstance, is held invalid by a court of
competent jurisdiction, the remainder of this Act and the application of its
provisions to other persons or circumstances shall not be affected.

(b) TITLE-LEVEL SEVERABILITY.-- Each Title of this Act is independently
operative and shall remain in full force and effect if any other Title or any
provision thereof is held invalid. In particular:

    (1) the invalidity of any provision of Title I concerning defense posture
    shall not affect the operative force of Titles II, III, or IV, which
    function independently of the specific defense posture transition
    timelines;

    (2) the invalidity of any provision of Title II concerning commons network
    security shall not affect the force structure transition of Title I or
    the automation governance provisions of Title IV; and

    (3) the invalidity of any provision of the Analytics Commons capture
    mechanism of Section 302 of Title III shall not affect the open-source
    analytics development program of Section 303 of that Title, which is
    independently operative.

(c) SEPARATION OF FUNCTIONS.-- The defense posture, commons security, analytics
commons, and automation governance functions of this Act are designed with
sufficient redundancy and independence that the invalidity of any specific
mechanism does not eliminate the broader function it serves, with alternative
pathways available through the governance infrastructure of the Federal
Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 505. JUDICIAL REVIEW.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FEDERAL COURT JURISDICTION.-- The federal district courts shall have
original jurisdiction over:

    (1) actions by Commons Members or Qualified Federated Networks challenging
    executive actions that violate the non-reinterpretation provision of
    Section 502(a) of this Title or that exceed the authority expressly
    conferred by this Act over the Federated Network;

    (2) actions by individuals challenging automated federal agency
    determinations that violate the Algorithmic Governance Prohibition of
    Section 404 of Title IV of this Act, pursuant to the private right of
    action established in Section 502(b)(3) of this Title;

    (3) actions by Qualified Federated Networks or Commons Members challenging
    domestic enclosure attempts as defined in Section 203(b) of Title II of
    this Act;

    (4) actions enforcing the foreign adversarial interference prohibitions
    of Section 202(a) of Title II of this Act; and

    (5) such other actions arising under this Act as present a federal question
    within the meaning of 28 U.S.C. section 1331.

(b) STANDING.-- Standing to bring actions under this Act shall be construed
broadly and consistently with the standing provisions of Section 1104(b) of
the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act. In addition:

    (1) any individual whose rights or benefits are materially affected by an
    automated determination in violation of Section 404 of Title IV of this
    Act shall have standing to challenge that determination regardless of
    whether the individual is a Commons Member;

    (2) any member of Congress shall have standing to challenge executive
    actions that violate the Resilience-Based Defense Posture declaration
    of Section 101 of Title I of this Act, in their capacity as a
    representative exercising constitutional oversight authority; and

    (3) the Analytics Commons Governance Council and the Automation Governance
    Council shall each have standing to bring enforcement actions within their
    respective governance domains under this Act.

(c) STANDARD OF REVIEW.-- In any action challenging executive action under
this Act:

    (1) the court shall apply de novo review without deference to the
    executive's interpretation of the Resilience-Based Defense Posture
    declaration or the missions no longer constituting primary defense
    policy under Section 101 of Title I of this Act;

    (2) any executive action asserting a national security justification for
    conduct that is otherwise prohibited under this Act shall be subject to
    searching judicial scrutiny rather than the traditional deference accorded
    executive national security determinations, on the grounds that this Act
    itself constitutes a congressional determination of what genuine national
    security requires and that executive reinterpretation of those
    requirements is not entitled to deference; and

    (3) the burden of demonstrating that any challenged action falls within
    the authority conferred by this Act shall rest with the Executive Branch.

(d) PRELIMINARY INJUNCTION STANDARD.-- In any action under this Act, the
court shall apply the modified preliminary injunction standard established in
Section 104(e)(4) of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives
Act, adapted as follows:

    (1) a showing that the challenged executive action violates the Resilience-
    Based Defense Posture declaration, the Algorithmic Governance Prohibition,
    or the commons network security provisions of this Act shall constitute a
    sufficient showing of likelihood of success on the merits;

    (2) any disruption to the Guaranteed Provision Standard of Commons Members
    caused by the challenged action shall constitute irreparable harm per se;
    and

    (3) the integrity and continuity of the commons transition established by
    this legislative program shall be deemed to constitute the public interest.

