SEC. 506. CONFORMING AMENDMENTS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) NATIONAL SECURITY ACT OF 1947.-- The National Security Act of 1947,
codified at 50 U.S.C. section 3001 et seq., is hereby amended to:

    (1) require that any presidential finding authorizing covert action under
    section 503 of that Act be assessed by the congressional intelligence
    committees against the covert interference prohibition of Section 104(c)
    of Title I of this Act, with a specific finding included in the
    notification to those committees that the authorized action is consistent
    with that prohibition;

    (2) add the protection of the Strategic Commons Infrastructure of the
    Federated Network to the definition of national security interests that
    the intelligence community is authorized to protect; and

    (3) designate the Analytics Commons Governance Council as an authorized
    recipient of unclassified threat intelligence relevant to the security
    of commons infrastructure, consistent with Section 204(c) of Title II
    of this Act.

(b) FOREIGN INTELLIGENCE SURVEILLANCE ACT.-- The Foreign Intelligence
Surveillance Act of 1978, codified at 50 U.S.C. section 1801 et seq., is
hereby amended to:

    (1) prohibit the use of any FISA authority for the bulk collection of
    communications metadata, content, or associated data of United States
    persons without individualized judicial authorization meeting the probable
    cause standard, consistent with the mass surveillance termination requirement
    of Section 104(b) of Title I of this Act; this prohibition supersedes any
    conflicting provision of the Act as it existed prior to the date of
    enactment of this Act, including any provision of Title VII of the Foreign
    Intelligence Surveillance Act (50 U.S.C. sections 1881 et seq.) permitting
    programmatic collection, and shall be given effect notwithstanding any
    pending reauthorization of such provisions;

    (2) provide that no FISA order, whether individual or programmatic, shall
    authorize the collection of data from the Federated Mesh, the National
    Resilience Ledger, or any other Federated Network infrastructure without
    meeting the heightened warrant standard established in Section 209(e)(3) of
    the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act; and

    (3) require the Attorney General to report to the congressional intelligence
    committees within ninety days of the date of enactment of this Act on all
    outstanding FISA orders authorizing bulk collection of the categories
    described in paragraph (1), the timeline for their vacation pursuant to
    Section 104(b)(4) of Title I of this Act, and any operational gaps created
    by their termination together with proposed individualized-authorization
    alternatives for each affected intelligence collection program.

(c) COMPUTER FRAUD AND ABUSE ACT.-- Section 1030 of Title 18, United States
Code, is hereby amended to incorporate the commons infrastructure sabotage
offense established in Section 207(a) of Title II of this Act as a specific
aggravated offense carrying the penalties established in that Section, in
addition to the existing anti-spoofing offense established by Section 1104(d)
of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act.

(d) ADMINISTRATIVE PROCEDURE ACT.-- The Administrative Procedure Act, codified
at 5 U.S.C. section 551 et seq., is hereby amended to:

    (1) require that any final agency action substantially generated by an
    automated system include, in the administrative record, documentation
    of the human review process through which the action was authorized,
    meeting the standards of Section 404(c) of Title IV of this Act; and

    (2) provide that any final agency action that fails to include the
    documentation required by paragraph (1) of this subsection is subject
    to automatic vacatur upon the application of any affected party, without
    requirement of further showing of prejudice.

(e) ENERGY POLICY ACT.-- The Energy Policy Act of 2005, codified at 42 U.S.C.
section 15801 et seq., is hereby amended to recognize cooperative energy
enterprises certified as Qualified Federated Cooperatives under the Federal
Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act as eligible recipients of
all federal energy development and infrastructure assistance programs, with
priority consideration in program allocation reflecting their role as
Strategic Commons Infrastructure under this Act.

(f) DEFENSE PRODUCTION ACT.-- The Defense Production Act of 1950, codified
at 50 U.S.C. section 4501 et seq., is hereby amended to:

    (1) recognize the Federated Network's cooperative energy, food, and
    manufacturing enterprises as defense production resources eligible for
    priority rating and allocation support in declared national emergencies,
    consistent with their designation as Strategic Commons Infrastructure
    under this Act; and

    (2) prohibit the use of Defense Production Act authority to compel any
    Qualified Federated Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network to produce,
    distribute, or allocate commons resources in ways inconsistent with the
    collective-choice governance processes of the Ostrom Standards of
    Stewardship, except in cases of declared war upon specific congressional
    authorization.

(g) FEDERAL ACQUISITION REGULATION.-- The Federal Acquisition Regulation shall
be amended, within two years of the date of enactment of this Act, to:

    (1) require federal agencies to give preference in procurement decisions
    to Analytics Commons tools and open-source automated systems over
    proprietary Intelligence-Community-Funded Analytics Platforms and
    proprietary automated decision systems, consistent with the procurement
    preference established under Section 302(d)(2) of Title III of this Act;
    and

    (2) require that all federal contracts for automated decision systems
    include a provision confirming compliance with the Algorithmic Governance
    Prohibition of Section 404 of Title IV of this Act, with the contracting
    agency responsible for verifying compliance at each contract renewal.

