SEC. 507. AUTHORIZATION OF APPROPRIATIONS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) GENERAL AUTHORIZATION.-- There are authorized to be appropriated to carry
out the purposes of this Act such sums as may be necessary for each fiscal year
following the date of enactment of this Act, subject to the specific
authorizations and funding mechanisms established in this Section.

(b) COMMONS INFRASTRUCTURE DEFENSE PROGRAM.-- There are authorized to be
appropriated to the Commons Infrastructure Defense Program established under
Section 102(c) of Title I of this Act:

    (1) not less than five hundred million dollars for the first fiscal year
    following enactment, for the threat assessment, program design, and initial
    capability deployment phases; and

    (2) not less than two hundred fifty million dollars for each subsequent
    fiscal year, for ongoing operations, network support, and the rapid
    response capability of Section 102(c)(4) of Title I of this Act.

(c) ANALYTICS COMMONS.-- There are authorized to be appropriated for the
establishment, development, and operation of the Analytics Commons:

    (1) not less than one billion dollars for the first fiscal year following
    enactment, covering the Intelligence-Community-Funded Analytics Platform
    audit and capture process, the initial open-source development program
    grants, the military logistics adaptation work, and the establishment of
    the Analytics Commons Governance Council;

    (2) not less than five hundred million dollars for each of the second
    through fifth fiscal years following enactment, for ongoing development,
    the Commons Adaptation Fund established under Section 304(d) of Title
    III of this Act, and the longitudinal data archive infrastructure; and

    (3) such sums as may be necessary for subsequent fiscal years, with the
    expectation that the Analytics Commons will be progressively self-sustaining
    through the commons economy's own financial architecture as the Federated
    Network matures.

(d) COMMONS ANALYTICS DEVELOPMENT PROGRAM.-- There are authorized to be
appropriated to the National Science Foundation for the Commons Analytics
Development Program established under Section 303 of Title III of this Act:

    (1) not less than two hundred fifty million dollars for the first fiscal
    year following enactment; and

    (2) not less than one hundred fifty million dollars for each of the second
    through fifth fiscal years following enactment.

(e) AUTOMATION GOVERNANCE.-- There are authorized to be appropriated for the
Automation Governance Council established under Section 406 of Title IV of
this Act and the federal agency automated system compliance program of Section
404(e) of that Title:

    (1) not less than one hundred million dollars for the first fiscal year
    following enactment, for the establishment of the Council and the initial
    federal agency compliance audit; and

    (2) not less than seventy-five million dollars for each subsequent fiscal
    year for ongoing Council operations and compliance monitoring.

(f) INTELLIGENCE REFORM.-- There are authorized to be appropriated for the
implementation of the intelligence reform provisions of Section 104 of Title
I of this Act, including the mass surveillance data deletion program, the
Inspector General compliance audit infrastructure, and the Privacy and Civil
Liberties Oversight Board annual review:

    (1) not less than two hundred fifty million dollars for the first fiscal
    year following enactment, for the data deletion program; and

    (2) not less than fifty million dollars for each subsequent fiscal year
    for ongoing oversight and compliance.

(g) FORCE STRUCTURE TRANSITION SAVINGS REDIRECT.-- The defense budget savings
realized through the force structure transition of Section 103 of Title I of
this Act shall be directed, in the percentages established in that Section,
to the Bootstrap Grant Program and the Commons Solidarity Fund of the Federal
Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, in addition to any
appropriations provided under that Act for those programs. The Secretary of
Defense and the Secretary of the Treasury shall jointly establish the accounting
mechanism for calculating and transferring these savings within one year of
the date of enactment.

(h) FUNDING PRINCIPLES.-- The appropriations authorized by this Section reflect
the front-loaded investment logic of this legislative program: the initial costs
of commons infrastructure development, intelligence reform, and defense posture
reorientation are transitional investments whose long-term fiscal return is
measured in reduced defense expenditure, reduced intelligence community
maintenance costs, and the productive contribution of a maturing commons economy
that no longer requires the petrodollar-protection commitments the prior posture
entailed. The Congressional Budget Office is directed to account for these
long-term fiscal returns in scoring the fiscal impact of this Act.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 508. EFFECTIVE DATE.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) GENERAL EFFECTIVE DATE.-- Except as otherwise provided in this Act, the
provisions of this Act shall take effect on the date of enactment.

(b) IMMEDIATE EFFECTIVE DATES.-- The following provisions shall take effect
immediately upon the date of enactment, with no phase-in period:

    (1) the Resilience-Based Defense Posture declaration of Section 101(a)
    and (b) of Title I of this Act;

    (2) the prohibition on the prohibited missions of Section 101(b) of
    Title I of this Act, applicable to all new commitments made after the
    date of enactment, with existing commitments subject to the phased
    transition of Section 103 of that Title;

    (3) the Algorithmic Governance Prohibition of Section 404 of Title IV
    of this Act, applicable to all new automated system deployments after
    the date of enactment, with existing deployments subject to the
    compliance timeline of Section 404(e) of that Title;

    (4) the foreign adversarial interference prohibitions and criminal
    penalties of Sections 202 and 207 of Title II of this Act;

    (5) the corporate capture prevention provisions of Section 206(c) of
    Title II of this Act; and

    (6) the Constitutional Safe Harbor of Section 503 of this Title,
    retroactive to the date of introduction of this Act in Congress.

(c) SCHEDULED EFFECTIVE DATES.-- The following provisions shall take effect
on the dates specified:

    (1) the doctrinal review requirement of Section 101(c) of Title I of
    this Act: completion within one year of enactment;

    (2) the mass surveillance termination requirement of Section 104(b) of
    Title I of this Act: one year after enactment;

    (3) the Open-Source Automation Mandate compliance timelines of Section
    403(b) of Title IV of this Act: as specified in that Section, beginning
    one year after enactment for energy systems;

    (4) the federal agency automated system compliance audit of Section
    404(e) of Title IV of this Act: completion within two years of enactment;

    (5) the Intelligence-Community-Funded Analytics Platform audit of Section
    302(b) of Title III of this Act: completion within one hundred eighty
    days of enactment; and

    (6) the Force Structure Transition Phase 1 savings redirect accounting
    mechanism of Section 507(g) of this Title: establishment within one
    year of enactment.

